<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barbados Beats Cuba In Shootout  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Barbados scored on all five of its penalty kicks in a
shootout,
beating Cuba 5-4 after a 1-1 tie Sunday and advancing in World Cup
qualifying.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbados will play in the semifinal round in a group that
includes the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Playing before a raucous home crowd at National Stadium in
Bridgetown, Barbados won when Cuba's Alexander Cruzada missed the
net on his penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Sergei Prado opened the scoring in the 77th minute,
finally making good on a furious assault on the Barbadian goal.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbados roared back one minute later, with Jerry Alexander
scoring on a ball chipped into the penalty area by Michael Forde.
</P>
<P>
   Play was stopped briefly with 12 minutes remaining after
spectators began throwing bottles at the Cuban bench, claiming
Cuban players had thrown objects into the stands. Police said they
were investigating the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Panama beat Nicaragua 4-0 to win its group, while St.
Vincent and the Grenadines finished first in its division with a
4-0 rout of Antigua and Barbuda.
Panama 4, Nicaragua 0:
</P>
<P>
   At Panama City, Julio Dely Valdes scored twice and the victory
gave Panama nine points in the Central America-Caribbean region.
Guatemala, which also has nine points, finished second.
</P>
<P>
   Dely Valdez scored at 60 and 70 minutes. Nefatali Diaz scored in
the 72nd and Roberto Brown in the 84th.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams ended with 10 men on the field after Nicaragua's
Norman Gonzalez and Panama's Ricardo Phillips were ejected.
St. Vincent 4, Antigua 0:
</P>
<P>
   At Kingstown, the hosts got two goals from Alwyn Guy.
</P>
<P>
   St. Vincent's first goal came from Vincent John in the 11th
minute. Wesley John put a shot home in the 50th minute, with Guy
making his contributions in the 56th and 61st minutes against
goalkeeper Jarneil Simon.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reversal of the May 7 match, when Antigua beat St.
Vincent 2-1. This time, the Vincentians dominated the game, giving
its own goalkeeper, Melville Andrews, little work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 0013 </TRAILER>
