<HEADLINE> National Zoo To Borrow New Pandas  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Panda House at the National Zoo, vacant
since giant panda Hsing-Hsing died six months ago, will get two new
residents under a 10-year, $10 million loan agreement with China.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese Embassy announced Sunday that Beijing has given
final approval to lend two giant pandas to the National Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined in a letter of intent signed April 7, the deal calls
for the Smithsonian Institution, which operates the zoo, to donate
$1 million a year for 10 years to China to essentially rent the
pandas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The two sides are firmly committed to the survival of giant
pandas and their habitats through habitat protection, scientific
research, public education, captive breeding, professional training
and other conservation biology measures,'' an embassy statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the $10 million payment for the loan of one male
and one female ''captive-born pre-productive'' giant panda will go
for research and conservation of the endangered black-and-white
animals.
</P>
<P>
   China will retain ownership of the new pandas, as well as any
offspring that result.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very pleased to learn of the decision from the Chinese
government and gratified at the speed with which they approved our
request,'' Smithsonian Institution Secretary Lawrence M. Small said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman David J. Umansky said the Smithsonian already has
received commitments of $5.8 million toward the $10 million cost.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speculate how long it will be before the two new
pandas take up residence in the Panda House. It has been empty
since last November, when the elderly Hsing-Hsing, suffering from
terminal kidney disease, was euthanized. His partner, Ling-Ling,
died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The pair produced several cubs, but none survived more than a
few days. Both pandas were given to the United States by China in
1972 and became the top attraction at the zoo, which draws some 3
million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Chinese officials still have to determine which male
and female pandas will be chosen, when they will be delivered and
other details. The next step for U.S. officials is to obtain an
import permit from the Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Only five giant pandas are in U.S. zoos -- three in San Diego and
two in Atlanta. Fewer than 1,000 live in the wild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
