<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lobbyists Cashing in as Advisers  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington insiders George W. Bush has
assembled to advise his Republican presidential campaign bring far
more to the table than just experience. Their lobbying firms
collected more than $34 million last year to influence the
government, federal filings show.
</P>
<P>
   Their clients range from America Online and Time Warner, who are
seeking federal permission to merge, to the American Association of
Health Plans, the group of managed care organizations trying to
defeat legislation giving patients the right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   The story is much the same for Bush's Democratic rival, Vice
President Al Gore, whose inner circle draws heavily on the advice
of former government officials-turned-lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the modern political arena, where former
government officials command big bucks as lobbyists and then are
summoned back during elections by presidential candidates needing
their experience.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the lobbyists' clients often become involved by
making big donations to the parties of their presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ''If George W. Bush wins, (the Republican lobbyists) all put
their children and their grandchildren through college because of
this windfall,'' said Charles Lewis, head of the Center for Public
Integrity, a government watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will become the most powerful, popular lobbyists in
Washington and they will stand to make millions of dollars because
of their perceived closeness to power.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the lobbying firm of Peter Knight, a
former top aide to Gore and manager of President Clinton's 1996
re-election campaign, was paid $1.5 million last year by such
clients as Lockheed Martin, the International Olympic Committee and
Schering-Plough. In 1995, Tennessee developer Franklin Haney,
trying to get the Federal Communications Commission to move to his
Portals development in Washington, paid Knight $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's firm has since disbanded and he is no longer lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   One lobbyist advising Texas Gov. Bush said his effort is about
being a good Republican, not an effort to improve his business.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are millions of Republicans supporting Governor Bush. I
am proud to be one of them,'' said Edward Gillespie, a former top
aide to House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At least a half-dozen other registered Washington lobbyists also
are on Bush's team. They include former Reps. Vin Weber and Bill
Paxon, former Republican National Chairman Haley Barbour, ex-White
House aides Kenneth Duberstein and Rick Davis and longtime
Washington political operative Charles Black.
</P>
<P>
   Weber, Duberstein and Davis switched their allegiance from Sen.
John McCain after the Arizona Republican withdrew from the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's inner circle also relies heavily on lobbyist-advisers.
</P>
<P>
   They include former Rep. Thomas Downey of New York, former
domestic policy adviser Greg Simon, former White House counsel Jack
Quinn and Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Their lobbying firms earned $9.6 million in fees last year from
such companies as General Motors, Boeing, Intel, MetLife and Bell
Atlantic, according to disclosure forms filed with the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Another Gore adviser, Roy Neel, heads the U.S. Telecom
Association, which represents independent phone companies and spent
$1.7 million lobbying the government last year.
</P>
<P>
   The seven lobbyists advising Bush work for firms that reported
receiving $34.2 million last year in fees to influence the
government. In addition to the entertainment giants and HMO group,
their clients include:
</P>
<P>
   --Philip Morris, one of the tobacco companies opposed to allowing
the Food and Drug Administration to regulate nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   --Microsoft, sued by the Justice Department on antitrust charges.
</P>
<P>
   --Bristol Myers-Squibb, which has a stake in the debate over
whether to expand Medicare benefits to cover prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bush said the advisers have impressive credentials that
earn them their position in the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are long-standing Republicans, held in high regard, who
have expertise to share on how to win back the White House,''
campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether his ties to Bush might be helpful in landing
clients, Gillespie said: ''I haven't even thought about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
