<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hatteras Lighthouse To Reopen  </HEADLINE>
By ESTES THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUXTON, N.C. (AP) -- Ten months after the Cape Hatteras
Lighthouse's majestic journey to a new home a half-mile from the
crashing Atlantic breakers, its keepers are spiffing it up for
well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   Floors and staircases are being swept and windows reinstalled in
anticipation of its official public reopening Friday. The 208-foot
lighthouse, the nation's tallest and best-known, has been closed to
visitors since Nov. 22, 1998. The move, costing $10 million and
spanning several weeks, was completed in July.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to sweep it out and wipe it down and make it
presentable before we let people in,'' Ranger Rob Bolling of the
National Park Service said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the lighthouse was moved, Hurricane Dennis flooded
the lighthouse grounds and blew sand into the structure.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the 4,800-ton lighthouse now sits 2,900 feet from
its former perch 150 feet from the ocean is a minor miracle.
</P>
<P>
   When it went into service in 1870, the lighthouse stood 1,600
feet from the ocean -- the same distance from the beach as now, but
over the decades erosion brought the ocean steadily closer.
</P>
<P>
   The move initially was fiercely opposed by Hatteras Island
residents, who feared the lighthouse might topple or that moving it
would dilute its historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Danny Couch, of Buxton, a leading opponent, salutes the
Park Service and its contractors for doing the job safely. Yet he
still believes the government could have stabilized the beach and
protected the lighthouse at its old site.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still think its impact was so much greater by the sea,''
Couch said. ''With it moved, I feel it does not have the same
historical and visual impact. It feels contrived to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But that view isn't shared by visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was relieved to hear they were going to do something,'' said
Michael Crowley of Richmond, Va. ''I resented all the opposition
from the local population. I thought it was kind of selfish.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cape Hatteras stands to a lot of people as America's
lighthouse. It's a national treasure, not a Dare County thing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The lighthouse was built before electricity was common in most
homes. Steam engines sucked water out of the hole dug for the
foundation, and oxen powered the pulleys that hoisted brick, tools
and men up the structure as it was built.
</P>
<P>
   When it was moved, the latest technology was employed. It was
severed from its foundation, jacked up and placed on a bed of
rollers. Hydraulic jacks slowly pushed it to its new home.
</P>
<P>
   Between 300,000 and 500,000 people came to watch the feat, named
the outstanding civil engineering achievement for 1999 by the
American Society of Civil Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Besides being an incredible engineering feat, this project
spoke volumes about the American spirit,'' said Francis Peltier,
superintendent of Cape Hatteras National Seashore.
</P>
<P>
   The lighthouse will be rededicated next May at a gathering of
descendants of Hatteras lighthouse keepers. A book of oral
histories about the lighthouse will be published to commemorate the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Drake, a visitor from Hendersonville, said he came to watch
the move last summer and ''marveled for two days.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the greatest engineering feat I've ever seen, and I've
seen the space shuttle launch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Cape Hatteras National Seashore:
https://www.nps.gov/caha/lrp.htm
</P>
<P>
   Outer Banks site:
https://www.outer-banks.com/hatteras-school/light.html
</P>
</TEXT>
