<DOCNO> APW20000522.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ralph Nader brings '60s activism to the 2000 campaign trail  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Running for president isn't much of a leap for
Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's most famous consumer activist has been campaigning
all his life, crusading since the 1960s for auto safety, clean air,
universal health care and a slew of other causes. Now he's jumped
into the Bush-Gore fray, seizing the chance to play his favorite
public role, thorn in the big guys' sides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here's who I'm running against -- the Bush corporation and the
Gore corporation,'' Nader said in a recent interview. ''These guys
are proxies for a corporate takeover of the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader is seeking the Green Party presidential nomination and
hopes to pull in the 5 percent of the vote needed to guarantee
federal matching funds for the party in 2004. He expects to be on
the ballot in at least 45 states and says he wants his campaign to
spur Americans to activism.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old Harvard-educated lawyer made his name as a
consumer advocate in 1965, when he published ''Unsafe At Any
Speed,'' a stinging critique of the auto industry that helped
prompt a federal law mandating seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's devoted himself almost single-mindedly to
battling what he sees as corporate domination of American life.
Marching under the banner of increased power for consumers and
citizens, he's fought for tougher environmental rules, government
openness, job safety, auto air bags and restrictions on lobbyists'
power, among scores of other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, whose close-cropped salt-and-pepper hair makes his
serious demeanor seem even more intense, has never married or had
children and is said by supporters to barely have a personal life.
Nearly all his energy has gone to his public crusades.
</P>
<P>
   His name has appeared on presidential ballots twice before, but
this is his most serious race. He was a write-in candidate in the
1992 New Hampshire primary. In 1996, the Greens put his name on
presidential ballots, but he hardly campaigned and received less
than 1 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes this bid will rouse Americans to take back a government
he believes has been sold outright to business interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to bring thousands of people ... into progressive
political activism,'' Nader said, leaning his lanky frame forward
over an office conference table. ''The key issue in this country
right now is whether we're going to have a democracy that places
the sovereignty of the people over the sovereignty of big
business.''
</P>
<P>
   That message may be a tough sell in a dot-com age, when many
young people seem more interested in stock options than political
action. But Nader believes that outside the ''contented classes''
at the top of the income pyramid, most Americans want a candidate
who'll shake up the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ''This message appeals to everybody who has a basic sense of
justice, who wants the country to move forward for all the
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's public profile peaked in the 1960s and '70s, when he
mentored the hundreds of young activists known as Nader's Raiders,
testified frequently before Congress and appeared on television
with investigations into corporate abuses.
</P>
<P>
   But in a political world that's moved well to the right since
then, his voice has gotten a lot lonelier.
</P>
<P>
   ''He gets the good, solid activist vote, but it ain't much,''
said Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK with Nader, who doesn't harbor serious hopes of taking
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of ways to define winning, and one of them is
building,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also scoffs at suggestions that by challenging Vice President
Al Gore on the left he'll help tip the election to Texas Gov.
George Bush. Nader said the Democrats long ago betrayed the liberal
ideals they once espoused, and he believes it makes little
difference which party is elected.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want to legitimize with your vote the least worst
choice ... then you are basically chaining yourself to both parties
getting worse every four years,'' Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   In states where one of the two major candidates seems to have a
clear lock, Nader added, liberal Democrats can vote for him without
worrying that they might help send Bush to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A recent CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll showed Nader and
ultra-conservative Reform Party hopeful Pat Buchanan each drawing
support from 4 percent of likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Miringoff, of Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion,
said Nader could benefit from voters' recent interest in renegade
candidates like Republican John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ''In certain states there can be an impact on Gore, and that's
something to be watched,'' Miringoff said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's signature issue, campaign finance reform, is also
central to Nader's agenda. He's raised about $600,000 for his own
effort so far and is aiming for $5 million, including federal
matching funds. He's also asking supporters to pledge hours to
volunteer with the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''The concept is citizen time will cancel out business bucks on
the other side,'' he explained. ''I want people to feel like we're
running with them, not parading in front of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 0234 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Von Trier Film Wins Palme d'Or  </HEADLINE>
By CLAR NI CHONGHAILE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France (AP) -- Danish director Lars von Trier and singer
Bjork celebrated joint triumphs and a truce after ''Dancer in the
Dark'' won the Palme d'Or in Cannes and the best actress award for
the Icelandic musician.
</P>
<P>
   After much talk of on-set tension between the unorthodox
director and his feisty leading lady, the two hugged to a standing
ovation Sunday at the film festival awards ceremony in the French
Riviera city.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a good night for Asian cinema, with the second-place
Grand Prize going to Chinese director Jiang Wen for ''Devils on the
Doorstep,'' a tragic yet funny tale about a Chinese village during
the Japanese occupation in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Best actor went to Hong Kong's Tony Leung for his role as a
cheated-on husband who embarks on his own affair in Wong Kar-wai's
''In the Mood for Love,'' while best director went to Taiwan's
Edward Yang for ''Yi Yi'' (A One and a Two).
</P>
<P>
   But all eyes were on Bjork and von Trier, whose well-publicized
feud sent a gossipy frisson through the 12-day festival.
</P>
<P>
   Von Trier punched the air as he accepted his award from French
legend Catherine Deneuve, who also starred in the movie -- easily
the most controversial film here this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dancer in the Dark'' tells the tale of Selma, a Czech
immigrant working in rural America in the 1960s. She is slowly
going blind and desperately saving to pay for an operation for her
son, who also risks losing his sight.
</P>
<P>
   But fate conspires against her and after a neighbor steals her
savings, she finds herself swept up in a horrific nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Critics were divided into those who loved the melodramatic tale
and those who hated it. The public was mainly interested in the
reported feuding, confirmed by von Trier -- who said before the
awards that the shooting had been ''terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a prize makes.
</P>
<P>
   At the post-awards news conference, Bjork giggled and playfully
punched von Trier, who was glowing happily.
</P>
<P>
   Bjork admitted the filming had been tough, and displayed an
eerie affinity with her character, whose only comfort in a cruel
world is her passion for classic Hollywood musicals.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old singer said music was her escape from the real
world, while acting brought reality back into focus.
</P>
<P>
   ''The film was very painful to do and all my records have been
very joyful ... it took me a while to get used to the suffering,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The rush of winning the prize made her forget all the pain. ''It
is a very, good magic potion you have here in Cannes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bjork's raw, emotional performance may have drained her, but it
won rave reviews and left many viewers in tears.
</P>
<P>
   No stranger to Cannes, von Trier won the Grand Prize for his
wrenching love story ''Breaking the Waves'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Among other awards was a special mention for the entire cast of
Pavel Lounguine's ''The Wedding,'' a lively tale of a boisterous
marriage in a Russian mining town.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian cinema garnered a clutch of awards. The jury prize was
tied between 20-year-old Samira Makhmalbaf of Iran for
''Blackboards and ''Songs from the Second Floor,'' by Swedish
director Roy Andersson, his first film in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   And the Golden Camera award for first-time director was given to
two Iranians, also in a tie: Hassan Yektapanah for ''Djomeh'' and
Bahman Ghobadi for ''A Time for Drunken Horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Best screenplay went to ''Nurse Betty,'' a dark, funny film
directed by Neil LaBute and written by John C. Richards and James
Flamberg. It was the only American film honored in the main
competition.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate competition, the star-studded ''Things You Can
Tell Just By Looking at Her,'' featuring Glenn Close, Cameron Diaz,
Holly Hunter and Calista Flockhart was the winner. The film was
directed by Rodrigo Garcia, the son of the celebrated Colombian
author Gabriel Garcia Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, headed by French director Luc Besson, ignored several
critically acclaimed films, including Liv Ullmann's ''Faithless,''
Joel and Ethan Coen's ''O Brother, Where Art Thou,'' and Aoyama
Shinji's nearly four-hour, black-and-white ''Eureka.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 0238 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
