<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, May 22, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S. Leone Rebels Free More Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Rebels in Sierra Leone have set free 54 more
U.N. captives after holding them hostage for nearly three weeks, a U.N. official
said. The peacekeepers were handed over to Liberian custody in the border town
of Foya on Sunday and flown by helicopter to Liberia's capital of Monrovia, said
U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst. They were brought to Freetown by plane a few
hours later. Many in the group looked thin and weak as they walked off the
plane. Three injured Kenyans among those released were taken away in an
ambulance.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Haitians Vote for New Government
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Haitians have voted peacefully in massive
numbers for the first time in years -- a cry for democracy by a people defying
fears of violence at the polls and a history of persecution. There were no
official participation figures, but Conyers estimated that up to 60 percent of
the 4 million-member electorate voted. Despite widespread relief at the relative
peace, hundreds of thousands of people were unable to vote because of alleged
technical difficulties that opposition leaders claimed were evidence of fraud by
the dominant Lavalas Party.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Violence Ebbs in West Bank, Gaza
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians are struggling to overcome the
deadly consequences of a week of violence that has int(AP) -- errupted peace
talks in Sweden and left a bitter aftertaste of distrust. Late Sunday, a
Palestinian teen shot during last week's clashes with Israeli troops died of his
injuries, the fifth Palestinian casualty of the violence. An Israeli toddler
remained in serious condition with severe burns after the car she was in was
attacked by firebombs in the West Bank.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No Survivors in Pensylvania Plane Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) -- After experiencing engine problems while trying to
land Sunday, a commuter plane carrying 19 people home from a gambling trip to
Atlantic City, N.J., crashed in a ball of fire. There were no survivors. Fiery
wreckage was spotted in some woods about 9 miles south of the
Wilkes-Barre/Scranton International Airport in northeastern Pennsylvania. It
appeared that both of the chartered turbo prop's engines failed, said Federal
Aviation Administration spokeswoman Tammy Jones. The plane missed its first
landing approach and crashed on its second attempt, said George Black of the
National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Demand for Workers Expected To Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Labor markets will remain tight this summer, with demand
for workers climbing to record heights as more than a third of American
companies anticipate hiring new employees, a new survey reports. In a survey of
16,000 companies, being released today by the temporary staffing agency Manpower
Inc., 35 percent said they plan to expand their work force in the third quarter,
while just 5 percent anticipated cutbacks. Fifty-five percent forecast no change
and 5 percent were uncertain.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Shuttle Astronauts Fix Broken Equipment
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Two spacewalking astronauts fixed broken
equipment Sunday night on the outside of the international space station, flying
united with the shuttle Atlantis. It was the shuttle crew's second 200-mile-high
feat of the day. The first was the impeccable shuttle-station linkup. Jeffrey
Williams and James Voss emerged from Atlantis a little early. The 5-foot
construction crane was installed on the space station by another pair of
spacewalkers last spring. But it was never locked properly into its socket,
allowing it to swivel back and forth.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Cigarette Exports Drop
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans are rejecting the smoking habit at a
surprisingly rapid rate, a trend that is going global. But there are signs of
increased smoking in poor countries and among teen-agers and young women in
several countries, and deaths blamed on smoking still are rising worldwide. U.S.
cigarette exports are down 25 percent, with 50 billion fewer cigarettes sent
abroad in just one year. That is 2.5 billion fewer packs of cigarettes exported
each year. The number of cigarettes sold per person in the United States fell a
record 8 percent last year, according to government data and to a Worldwatch
analysis.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 472.16 points to close at 16,386.01. 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubs 4, Reds 2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Kevin Tapani came within two outs of a shutout and the
Chicago Cubs used a wild throw from Cincinnati catcher Eddie Taubensee to score
two sixth-inning runs Sunday and beat the Reds 4-2. Chicago won two of three
games in the series that did not feature a home run from either Sammy Sosa or
Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
