<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio begins Senate campaign on talk shows and hurried upstate tour </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEEKTOWAGA, N.Y. (AP) -- Five Rick Lazio supporters held up blue
cardboard letters Sunday while awaiting the newly announced U.S.
Senate candidate's first campaign visit upstate.
</P>
<P>
   ''See, they're spelling his name, honey,'' Mary Beth Cerrone
pointed out to her 9-year-old-son, Dominic. ''L-A-Z-I-O.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lesson Lazio must now teach the rest of the state as the
largely unknown Republican picks up where New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani left off in the GOP's pursuit of Daniel Patrick
Moynihan's Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Wasting no time after announcing his candidacy in his high
school gym Saturday, Lazio scheduled hurried visits to Buffalo,
Rochester, Syracuse and Binghamton after making the rounds on the
Sunday morning television talk show circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Yorkers will not have to worry about who Rick Lazio is and
what his ambition is,'' Lazio told supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never needed an exploratory committee to find western New
York or figure out where I want to live,'' he said in one of
several swipes at Hillary Rodham Clinton's non-New York roots,
already a favored topic in his campaign against the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   The four-term Congressman used 15- to 30-minute stops in the
upstate cities to tell a condensed version of his life story,
introduce his wife, Patricia, and two young daughters, and credit
his military parents for instilling ''bedrock values'' of family,
work and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the values of New York and those are the values I'm
going to bring to the U.S. Senate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of the hopes and dreams that you have for your children
and grandchildren,'' he said, ''I have for mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, 42, said he will stand on his ''mainstream record that
fits the thinking of the vast majority of the people of our state''
and described himself as a fiscal conservative, committed
environmentalist and small-government conservative who supports a
woman's right to choose but not a procedure opponents call
''partial-birth abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a family supporter, here with my family, who dreams of a
culture that helps parents trying to raise their children and
rejects the corrupting pollution of thoughtless violence on
television and the movies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, Lazio, who broke with his party to support the
Brady Bill, said he supports ''reasonable measures to support the
rights of sportsmen while aggressively protecting our children from
the illegal use of handguns.''
</P>
<P>
   He promised to be a frequent visitor upstate, addressing a
concern of voters who complained they did not see enough of
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to be here so often I'm going to be sweating Buffalo
wings,'' he told 150 Buffalo-area supporters who greeted him with
chants of ''New York Lazio'' and hastily made campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   After Lazio made a similar promise in Rochester, Steve Minarik,
chairman of the Monroe County Republican party, said he expects
Lazio to do better upstate than Giuliani would have.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Rick Lazio has a better understanding of what it's
going to take to represent upstate New York,'' Minarik said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm more excited. I like underdogs. He's a nice guy ... I like
guys who care,'' Minarik said.
</P>
<P>
   At a third stop at Syracuse's Hancock International Airport,
Lazio was met by supporters for both him and his opponent, all
jockeying for position with their campaign signs. One person would
hold up a Hillary sign and a Lazio sign would go up in front of it.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio emphasized being a native New Yorker and his record during
his talk. He appeared with his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected liberal groups from outside New York to join
Hillary Clinton against him and to that he said, ''Bring them on.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he presented voters with a clear choice compared to
Mrs. Clinton, whom he identified as a ''big-spending liberal,'' who
is presently trying to ''repackage'' herself. ''Hillary Clinton is
no more a new Democrat than a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hillary Clinton supporter said the group showed up to show
their support.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCandless, from Syracuse, said, ''Just because someone is
not from New York doesn't mean they can't do the job. Think about
it, how many people living in New York were actually born here?
What are we doing, discriminating against anyone who wasn't born
here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
