<HEADLINE> Nasdaq at Low for Year; Dow Down 65  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index slid to its low point
for the year today as investors sold technology stocks on the fear
that their earnings will be hammered as interest rates creep
higher.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq
composite index was down 113.98 at 3,276.42, well below its lowest
close of the year --3,321.29 on April 14, when the index sustained a
devastating 355.49-point drop.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 64.77 at 10,562.08,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 12.39 at 1,394.56.
</P>
<P>
   Bellwether technology companies were continuing a long, steady
slide that has knocked the Nasdaq composite index 35 percent below
its March 10 record. Intel fell 1| to 116\ and Cisco Systems fell 2
1/16 to 51].
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors appear to have determined that with
interest rates on the rise, the high price of technology stocks may
not be justified by their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Federal Reserve raised rates for the sixth time
since last June. Recent economic reports have offered a mixed
report on whether the Fed's rate increases are successfully slowing
the economy, and the next major report won't hit the market until
Thursday, when the Commerce Department issues a preliminary report
on the gross domestic product during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors led the Dow lower, tumbling 7 15/16 to 79 1/16.
The company is allowing shareholders to swap stock for shares in
Hughes Electronics, a wholly owned subsidiary. The deal is
ultimately expected to boost GM's stock price, and will reduce the
number of GM shares on the market, driving GM's earnings per share
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 98.02 million shares,
well behind Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 9.13 to 470.57.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.8 percent as
leading technology stocks fell steeply. In afternoon trading,
Germany's DAX index was down 0.5 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
up 0.5 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
