<HEADLINE> Plane crashes, kills all 19 people aboard  </HEADLINE>
By TINA MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) -- Investigators will focus on why two
engines of a commuter plane carrying 19 people from a weekend trip
to Atlantic City reportedly failed at the same time, federal
transportation officials said today.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board member George Black said
engines failing simultaneously is ''highly improbable'' and could
indicate some sort of systems failure, including fuel
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ''Water is always a worry, but there could be other contaminants
in the fuel,'' Black said today. ''We are trying to find where the
aircraft was last refueled and pull information. Hopefully, we can
get samples there. But yes, we are looking at fuel and fuel
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed at 11:48 a.m. Sunday on its second approach to
the Wilkes-Barre/Scranton International Airport. The 17 passengers
and two pilots were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots told air traffic controllers they were experiencing
engine trouble on the second approach to the airport. Black said
foggy and rainy weather may have led to the twin-engine turbo prop
missing its first approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no mention of any emergency or engine problem until
the second approach,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The BA-31 Jetstream was owned by Executive Airlines of
Farmingdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Peragine, Executive's chief executive officer, said
today that the pilot had 8,500 hours of flight time, including
4,000 hours on the type of plane that crashed, and the first
officer was close to being upgraded to pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ''These were two expert pilots and the machine was maintained to
the highest standards. You just don't have a clue as to what could
have possibly happened,'' Peragine said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane had left the Atlantic City Airport about 10:30 a.m.
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hartt, spokesman for the South Jersey Transportation
Authority, which operates the airport, said the aircraft received
no maintenance or fuel there after arriving Sunday morning from
Republic Airport in Farmingdale. A telephone message left at
Republic Airport was not immediately returned today.
</P>
<P>
   Burned and twisted wreckage was scattered across a swath of
forest about 9 miles south of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of the victims were pulled from thick woods and
taken over dirt roads in the mountains to an airport hangar for
identification today. The passengers were believed to be from the
area around Wilkes-Barre and Scranton, two nearby cities in
northeastern Pennsylvania, about 90 miles north of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''These were people who were very much loved in our community,''
Scranton Mayor Jim Connors said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the tragedy had shaken this region that is surrounded by
dense forests and pristine lakes, popular for camping and hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers were on a short gambling trip to Atlantic City on
a plane chartered by a casino. The plane had departed for New
Jersey at 5 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and friends filed into the airport throughout the day
Sunday. Many of them dabbed their eyes as they left the building,
where they received consolation from clergy and counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials joined them in an airport building occupied by
the Red Cross. They gathered around tables, talking and offering
support to each other, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Airport Superintendent Jim Brunozzi said his niece's
mother-in-law and father-in-law were among the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was tough to look at the manifest and see the names,''
Brunozzi said. ''We were a close family. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony J. Giannone, airport ground superintendent, had to
console a friend whose wife was on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got two small kids, and he had to leave here to tell
them,'' Giannone said.
</P>
<P>
   Wy A. Gowell, the airport's assistant director, said the group
had taken a flight chartered by Caesars Atlantic City Hotel Casino.
They were to return at 1:15 a.m., but fog kept the plane grounded
in Farmingdale, N.Y., so they spent Saturday night at the hotel,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Maguire was outside gardening at her home near the airport
on the northern rim of the Pocono Mountains when she heard a plane
apparently having problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard the engines die, then I heard them start up again, and
then they just died. I heard it rev up twice, so it died twice,''
Maguire said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
