<HEADLINE> Court Throws Out Tobacco Biz Appeal  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected the tobacco
industry's attempt to replace the Florida judge presiding over the
nation's only statewide lawsuit seeking damages for hundreds of
thousands of people with smoking-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that threw out
cigarette makers' objection to Judge Robert Kaye's role in the
case. Their appeal said Kaye is an ex-smoker with a heart ailment --
and therefore a member of the ''class'' of an estimated 500,000
people who could share in any monetary award.
</P>
<P>
   A trial jury in Miami already has found that the tobacco
companies conspired to sell a dangerous product and should pay
$12.7 million in compensatory damages. Opening statements begin
this week in the trial's last stage, in which the jury must decide
whether to award punitive damages to punish the companies for their
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stakes are immense: the class ... seeks compensatory and
punitive damages in excess of $200 billion,'' the justices were
told. ''It is wholly inconsistent with the most fundamental notions
of fairness to have this precedent-setting, multi-billion dollar
case tried by a judge who will be eligible to receive a substantial
recovery himself if the plaintiffs prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in 1994, and Kaye has presided over it
since 1998. After the trial began, Kaye was hospitalized for an
angioplasty to correct a blocked artery. The tobacco companies'
lawyers said they thereafter discovered, apparently from news media
stories, that Kaye was a former smoker.
</P>
<P>
   They sought to have Kaye disqualified but he and a Florida
appeals court rejected their attempt.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking help from the nation's highest court, the tobacco
companies' lawyers said, ''No principle of our judicial system is
more fundamental or has a more established pedigree than the
requirement of a neutral and disinterested decisionmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Their appeal was supported in a friend-of-the-court brief
submitted by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for those who are suing the tobacco companies said there
is ''no admissible or credible evidence established that Judge Kaye
is a member of the class.'' They said the cigarette makers ''have
taken innuendo, rumor and gossip ... to form a false premise.''
</P>
<P>
   Named as defendants in the Florida lawsuit are Philip Morris
Inc., R.J. Reynolds, Brown &AMP; Williamson, Lorillard Tobacco Co.,
Liggett and the industry's Council for Tobacco Research and Tobacco
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Philip Morris vs. Engle, 99-1277.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 1046 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Sets Aside 'Touching' Ruling  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today set aside a ruling
that said any unwanted sexual touching is a ''crime of violence''
covered by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, who last week struck down as unconstitutional key
provisions of the federal Violence Against Women Act, told a
federal appeals court to reconsider a Utah dispute over the scope
of related provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court presumably will dismiss the Utah case.
</P>
<P>
   In its May 15 decision, the nation's highest court said Congress
overstepped its authority when it gave rape victims the right to
sue their attackers in federal court. The court, by a 5-4 vote,
said states, not Congress, should provide such help for victims of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   In the Utah case, the appeals court previously ruled that women
could invoke the law when suing over unwanted sexual advances that
violate a state's criminal sexual abuse law.
</P>
<P>
   Three women sued their former boss, Bryon Rosquist, over his
alleged conduct during their employment. The 1997 federal lawsuit
filed by Melanie McCann, Noele Nelson and Lisa Nielson said
Rosquist, a chiropractor in Provo, repeatedly fondled and rubbed
their buttocks, breasts and genital areas without their consent.
Rosquist denied all the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   A federal trial judge ruled that the women could not invoke the
federal law because they had not alleged any violence. But the 10th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals revived the lawsuit last August.
</P>
<P>
   ''In enacting the VAWA (Violence Against Women Act), Congress
recognized the degree to which our nation's systems of law
enforcement and adjudication have been complicit in perpetuating
the epidemic of violence against women, in part by failing to
recognize crimes of gender-motivated violence as serious crimes,''
a three-judge panel of the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not compound that failing,'' it added, ''by
restricting ... the definition of violence to only those forms of
violence most traditionally feared by men -- murder and serious
bodily injury. To do otherwise would be to perpetrate ... the very
judicial indifference to gender-based violence that Congress has
endeavored to obviate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosquist's Supreme Court appeal said many states do not include
nonconsensual sexual touching in their definitions of violent sex
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Rosquist vs. McCann, 99-1227.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 11th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 1050 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Narrows Whistle-Blower Law  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today narrowed a key
whistle-blower law, saying people cannot use it to file lawsuits
that accuse a state of cheating the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 ruling in a Vermont case upheld the basic right of
private citizens to file fraud lawsuits on the federal government's
behalf. But the justices said federal law protects the states from
being sued.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, private citizen whistle-blowers' lawsuits have
helped the government recover more than $3.5 billion from companies
that allegedly defrauded the taxpayers, according to the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hold that a private individual has standing to bring suit
in federal court on behalf of the United States under the False
Claims Act,'' Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the court, ''but
that the False Claims Act does not subject a state (or state
agency) to liability in such actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from the 1863 federal False Claims Act, which
allows private citizens to file lawsuits on the federal
government's behalf alleging that private companies -- usually an
employer -- committed fraud against the government.
</P>
<P>
   People whose lawsuits are successful can collect a share of any
damages awarded. The Justice Department says the government has
turned over $550 million of the $3.5 billion recovered to the
private whistle-blowers. Most of the damages go to the U.S.
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous such lawsuits have been filed over the years alleging
fraud by defense contractors, for example, or contractors for
health care programs such as Medicare and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration asked the justices to decide private
citizens can file such lawsuits, arguing that the government
legally can assign its claims to other people to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Today's case reverses a federal appeals court decision that had
let a Vermont man use the law to pursue a whistle-blower case
against a state agency that had employed him. Jonathan Stevens,
formerly a lawyer for the state Agency of Natural Resources' water
supply division, alleged that the agency had submitted false time
records in connection with federal grant programs.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont officials argued that the state should not be considered
a ''person'' who could be sued under the false-claims law. They
also invoked the Constitution's 11th Amendment, which the court has
interpreted to generally bar states from being sued by individuals
in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   A trial judge let the case go forward, and the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four states supported Vermont's appeal to the Supreme
Court, arguing in a friend-of-the-court brief that states could be
subject to huge penalties if such whistle-blower lawsuits could be
filed against them.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court agreed last June to hear the state's appeal.
But in a surprising order issued just 10 days before the Nov. 30
argument, the justices decided to broaden the case and consider
whether private citizens can sue anyone on the federal government's
behalf, whether or not a state.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Scalia wrote that there was a ''long tradition'' of such
lawsuits in England and the American colonies.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the False Claims Act does not include states as
''persons'' who can be sued under the law. The court did not decide
whether the Constitution's 11th Amendment also protects states from
being sued under the law, but Scalia said there was ''a serious
doubt on that score.''
</P>
<P>
   His opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, Clarence Thomas
and Stephen Breyer. Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg filed a separate
opinion, saying she understood the decision to leave open the
question whether the federal government can sue states under the
False Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens and David H. Souter dissented from
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the two, Stevens said the law ''makes it perfectly
clear'' that Congress intended to allow lawsuits against states.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Vermont Agency of Natural Resources vs. U.S.,
98-1828.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For current Supreme Court decisions:
http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/ and click on ''this month's
decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
