<DOCNO> APW20000522.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver critic says he will air grievances today  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York's three top statewide elected
Democrats said today the power struggle between the state
Assembly's former majority leader Michael Bragman and Speaker
Sheldon Silver had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ''The battle for leadership of the Assembly is over,'' U.S. Sen.
Charles Schumer, state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer and state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall declared in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now they have resolved it, the Democratic Party can build on
the success and unity of the state convention in Albany,'' the
three top Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman had filed notice last week to formally challenge Silver
for the speakership in the Democrat-dominated Assembly. But a
number of defections have reduced what he once counted as 53
Democrats ''rock-solid'' behind him becoming speaker to
''several,'' and Bragman said he does not know if his resolution
challenging Silver will even get to a floor vote today.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the suburban Syracuse lawmaker vowed to continue his
overthrow-Silver fight as an anti-Silver campaign. Bragman and his
supporters have formed the Assembly Majority Reform Caucus to
address the issue, and they scheduled an afternoon news conference
to discuss the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the very least, I intend to make a very comprehensive
statement tomorrow, spelling out why this happened, what has
happened and where I intend to go at this point,'' Bragman said
Sunday evening. ''If anybody thinks I intend to go away, that's
something they should not think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said there is a wellspring of discontent among the 98
Assembly Democrats -- only temporarily staunched by strong-arm
lobbying tactics by Silver, he argued -- who believe the speaker is
secretive and autocratic.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman blamed his eroding support on Silver allegedly
threatening to run other Democrats in primaries this year against
incumbents not supporting the speaker, or to draw new district
lines for the 2002 elections so that they could not hope to hold
their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the pressure Silver placed on opponents, Bragman
said Sunday it is something of a miracle the ex-majority leader has
anyone still willing to stand by him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The members who withstood this harassment and bludgeoning are
the most courageous members I have come across,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the crisis over, Silver held a buffet and strategy
session Sunday night at the Capitol for the 50 ''core'' members he
believed were behind him all the way in the power struggle against
Bragman. Other Democratic assemblymen, their allegiances more
suspect, were to meet with the speaker today.
</P>
<P>
   A last straw, of sorts, to Bragman's hopes came Sunday when
Queens Democratic leader Thomas Manton and Silver had breakfast
together in Manhattan to try to clear the air over their
long-standing feud. They issued a joint statement afterward
promising a ''new partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This new era of goodwill begins with support for Sheldon
Silver as speaker of the New York state Assembly,'' the two
politicians said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost exactly four days earlier, Manton had stood at an Albany
news conference promoting Bragman as Silver's replacement. ''I
believe he's lost the confidence of his members,'' Manton said of
Silver at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The rapprochement reached Sunday effectively meant Bragman could
not count on any of the 15 Democratic Assembly members from Queens
to back him against Silver. But Bragman said he held no ill will
toward Manton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tom Manton has been a gentleman throughout this process, a
partner I hold in the highest regard,'' Bragman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another blow to Bragman's hopes of toppling Silver was dealt by
Bronx Democratic leader Roberto Ramirez, who is also an
assemblyman, when he sided with Silver last Thursday. Bragman had
been trying to woo him to his camp.
</P>
<P>
   And, Bragman appeared to be counting on far more help from
McCall -- he called him his ''partner'' last Wednesday when
announcing the coup attempt -- than he got. Bragman has been an
early and vocal supporter of McCall's likely run for governor in
2002 against Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said McCall called him on Saturday to say it was not in
the comptroller's best interests to take sides in the emotional and
divisive Assembly leadership fight. That had roughly the same
effect as a statement issued by the leadership of many of the
state's most powerful unions on Thursday saying this was not a good
time for a power struggle atop the Democratic Assembly. Both
pronouncements effectively supported retaining the status quo,
meaning Sheldon Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman told the Syracuse Post-Standard Saturday he never had an
agreement that McCall would back Bragman against Silver, ''but he
was going to bring in key support.'' Bragman added, ''He, and he
alone, could have turned it around.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCall and his aides insisted throughout that the
comptroller, the only black ever elected to statewide office in New
York and an influential voice among minority legislators,
considered the Bragman-Silver struggle an internal Assembly matter.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he still supports McCall for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, from suburban Syracuse, was stripped of his majority
leader's title, his $34,500-a-year stipend and the vast resources
that go with the majority leader's office.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted Sunday night he knew the potential hazards of
his actions and was comfortable with his new lot in the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the first time in many years I feel absolutely free, free
to say anything that is necessary to bring reform to this house,''
Bragman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
