<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Must Share Desegregation Costs  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court, rejecting an appeal by New
York officials, today refused to spare the state from having to pay
half the $85 million-per-year costs of racially integrating public
schools in Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings requiring the
state to share costs of a desegregation plan that includes magnet
schools, voluntary busing, school closings and staff reassignments
for the city's 24,000-student school district.
</P>
<P>
   The state's appeal had argued that the city, just north of New
York City, and its school district pay for the desegregation
efforts on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal said a federal appeals court ruling in the Yonkers
case may lead other courts to ''impose novel and expansive
liability on the states for the unconstitutional acts of their
municipal subdivisions and local school districts.''
</P>
<P>
   It added: ''The issues presented ... are of vast importance to
the state of New York and to states throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The long legal dispute over racial desegregation of Yonkers
schools dates back to 1980, when the federal government sued the
city and local school board, alleging civil rights violations in
education and housing.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled in 1985 that Yonkers officials
intentionally and unlawfully promoted racial segregation through
their housing and school policies. He ordered the city to
desegregate the school system and build subsidized housing in
predominantly white sections of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The case attracted national attention when in 1988 four defiant
city councilmen were threatened with jail as well as fines, and the
city faced possible bankruptcy, for refusing the judge's orders.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing contempt-of-court fines against the councilmen were
overturned by a 5-4 Supreme Court decision in 1990. But the city
treasury had to pay heavy fines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the Yonkers school board sought to have the state held
partially liable, contending that inaction by the state government
held back integration efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Protracted litigation over the state's involvement ended in
court rulings that the state could be forced to help pay for
remedies because it ''failed to take corrective measures.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest decision requiring state participation in paying for
desegregation came last November when a three-judge panel of the
2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld ''apportioning costs ...
equally between the state and Yonkers.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is New York vs. Yonkers Board of Education, 99-1370.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 2nd Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
