<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Studies Laws' Retroactivity  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to use a
Tennessee murder case to clarify when judicial rulings that stiffen
criminal laws can be applied to acts that occurred earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said they will hear a Tennessee man's argument that
he was wrongly convicted of murder because the victim lived more
than a year after the assault occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbert K. Rogers contends Tennessee's traditional ''year and a
day'' law barred people from being convicted of murder in such
cases. But a Tennessee court canceled the law and said that
cancellation could be applied retroactively to his case because it
was a foreseeable change in law.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Rogers stabbed James Bowdery in the chest on May
7, 1994. Shortly afterward, Bowdery suffered a heart attack and
brain damage. He survived in a vegetative state until August 1995,
when he died of a kidney infection related to the coma.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was convicted in Shelby County of second-degree murder
and sentenced to 33 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' appeal to the Tennessee Court of Criminal Appeals relied
on the ''year and a day'' rule, which he said had been declared
binding law by state courts. However, the appeals court said the
rule was canceled when the state codified its criminal laws in 1989
without including it.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Supreme Court said the 1989 state criminal code
did not abolish the rule, and that it was in force when the Bowdery
assault occurred.
</P>
<P>
   However, the state's top court also said the rule was no longer
justified, and it canceled the rule. Further, the court said that
cancellation could be applied retroactively to Rogers' case because
it was not unexpected. Therefore, the court upheld his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, Rogers' lawyer said applying the
ruling retroactively to his case violated his due-process rights
under the Constitution's Fifth and 14th Amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee prosecutors said the state court ruling ''was not an
unforeseeable judicial enlargement of a criminal statute'' and
therefore it could be applied to Rogers' case.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Supreme Court threw out a Texas man's
sex-assault convictions that were based on a law enacted after he
allegedly committed the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Today's case is Rogers vs. Tennessee, 99-6218.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
