<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio picks up backing of Conservative leader; Clinton gets Liberal boss </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- In a crucial development for his fledgling
Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton, Rep. Rick Lazio
picked up the backing today of state Conservative Party Chairman
Michael Long.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican running for statewide office has won since 1974
without Conservative Party support in New York. The backing can
make the difference in a close race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think his chances are really excellent,'' Long said this
morning in announcing his support for the congressman from Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the boss of the state's Liberal Party came out ''100
perecent'' behind the first lady's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no doubt she will emerge as the candidate of the
Liberal Party,'' Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding said late
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   No Democrat has been elected governor or U.S. senator in New
York without Liberal Party backing since the party was founded in
1944.
</P>
<P>
   Harding has been a top political adviser to Rudolph Giuliani,
the Republican New York City mayor who dropped out of the Senate
race on Friday to deal with his prostate cancer. That opened the
door for Lazio to jump into the Senate race on the GOP side and
cleared the way for Harding to get behind Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The backing of Long for Lazio and Harding for Clinton is
expected to set the stage for their nominations, respectively, by
the third parties on June 3 when they hold their state nominating
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Long's backing of Lazio came after former U.S. Rep. Joseph
DioGuardi told the party chairman that he would not continue with
his quest for the Conservative Party's Senate nomination. DioGuardi
had entered the fray because of his policy disagreements with
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Long had refused to get behind Giuliani's Senate bid because of
the New York City mayor's refusal to come out in favor of a ban on
a late-term abortion procedure that critics call ''partial-birth
abortion'' and the mayor's strong ties to the state's Liberal
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, while maintaining he is an abortion rights supporter,
favors banning the abortion procedure and has never run with
Liberal Party backing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Republican George Pataki beat three-term Democratic
incumbent Mario Cuomo in the governor's race on the strength of the
vote on the Conservative Party line. Unlike other states, New York
allows major party candidates to also count votes from third-party
ballot lines.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing he has a lot of ground to cover to get his nascent
Senate campaign up and running, Lazio hit the ground running Sunday
in a whirlwind tour, determined to overcome the biggest immediate
obstacle in his quest to beat Clinton: his own obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio flew to Buffalo, Rochester, Syracuse and Binghamton
Sunday, stopping for about 30 minutes in each town to rally support
for his Senate run. He planned to visit Elmira, Watertown, Utica,
Albany and Westchester County today.
</P>
<P>
   Early on Sunday, Lazio appeared on six television talk shows and
gave the commencement address at a Long Island college.
</P>
<P>
   ''My challenge is to make sure that people know the real Rick
Lazio before the other side gets out and tries to fool the New York
people about who I am,'' Lazio said on CNN's ''Late Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he wasn't troubled by a new Zogby poll that showed
Clinton ahead, 46 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect to be behind for a long time,'' Lazio told reporters
as he left the New York Institute of Technology in Old Westbury, on
Long Island. ''I expect to be the underdog throughout this race.''
</P>
<P>
   While upstate, Lazio told a condensed version of his life story,
introduced his wife and two daughters and credited his military
parents for instilling ''bedrock values'' of family, work and
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised to be a frequent visitor upstate, addressing a
concern of voters who complained they did not see enough of
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spent Sunday in Albany and Troy, scolded Lazio for
using his campaign announcement a day earlier to attack her as a
liberal carpetbagger with political ambitions beyond the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a little disappointed yesterday that my latest opponent
has already started hurling insults instead of offering ideas about
what we can do to improve the lives of New Yorkers,'' Clinton said.
''Every candidate has to make a decision about what kind of
campaign he or she will run. Will it be a campaign of ideas and
issues or a campaign of insults? ... I am sorry that my opponent
could not even get through his announcement speech without going on
the attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign adviser Harold Ickes, campaign manager Bill
deBlasio and spokesman Howard Wolfson on Sunday's talk shows
portrayed Lazio as a lieutenant of Newt Gingrich and said his
support of the Contract with America was out of step with the
mainstream of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio defended his position rather than trying to distance
himself from it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know which one of the things on the Contract with
America that they are against,'' Lazio told ''Late Edition.'' ''Is
it the balanced budget? Is it lowering taxes? Is it a strong
national defense? If that's what they're against and I'm for, I'm
comfortable fighting on those grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the series of television interviews, Lazio sought to define
himself as ''just a plain old New Yorker'' -- native of Long Island,
son of an auto-parts dealer, married with two small children who
attend public school.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by ''Fox News Sunday'' if there were any skeletons in his
closet, like drug or health problems, he said: ''I'm clean as a
whistle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
