<HEADLINE> 'Million Dollar Man' turns against wrestling  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) -- As a professional wrestler, Ted DiBiase was
the 'Million Dollar Man' who would enter the ring wearing a tuxedo
and diamond-encrusted belt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 46-year-old DiBiase won't let his kids watch the sport
that made him rich. His motto when he was wrestling was ''Every man
has his price.'' His new motto is, ''You've got to walk the walk
(when it comes to faith).''
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you think Jesus would sit down in your living room and
watch 'Smackdown'?'' he asked a crowd at the YMCA here Saturday
night, referring to the raucous but very popular WWF TV show.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBiase said he still does some pro wrestling commentary.
</P>
<P>
   But, he conceded, his wrestling spirit died hard.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't take the wrestler out of the man,'' he said. ''(Now)
I'm an in-your-face Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   For five years, DiBiase was ''The Million Dollar Man,'' a WWF
villain, who, when he could not win, attempted to buy success. Now,
he said, his wrestling days are definitely over.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll never see me in Spandex again, I promise you,'' DiBiase
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
