<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq at Low for Year; Dow Off 240  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index fell to its low point
for the year today as investors sold technology stocks on fears
that earnings will be hurt by rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was
down 176.47 at 3,213.93, well below its lowest close of the year
--3,321.29 on April 14, when the index sustained a devastating
355.49-point drop. In earlier trading today, the Nasdaq was down
more than 200 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 239.88 at 10,386.97,
having also recovered from an earlier 200-point drop. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 33.40 at 1,373.55.
</P>
<P>
   Bellwether technology companies were continuing a long, steady
slide that has knocked the Nasdaq composite index 35 percent below
its March 10 record. Intel fell 5 1/16 to 112 13/16 and Cisco
Systems fell 2 5/16 to 51[.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors appear to have determined that with
interest rates on the rise, the high price of technology stocks may
not be justified by their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the correction for technology stocks still has
further to go,'' said Thomas McManus, equity portfolio strategist
at Banc of America Securities in New York. Even the bellwether
names, which attracted investors in the wake of April's technology
selloff, are now under escalating pressure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had suggested that investors increase the quality and
liquidity of tech stock holdings in anticipation of a sharp
correction, but the risk remains that technology blue-chips become
increasingly overvalued and overowned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq hasn't traded this low since last November, when the
index hit an intraday low of 3,124.77. That marked the start of an
incredible upward path for the index, which ended the year with an
86 percent gain -- the steepest in history for any major stock
index.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts are holding to the view that the current weakness
is washing out the rampant exuberance that dominated the market at
the close of 1999 and in early 2000. But with the damage mounting,
investors are struggling to determine which technology stocks -- if
any -- are worthy of their still-high prices.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's greatest obstacle remains rising interest
rates, analysts said. Last week, the Federal Reserve raised rates
for the sixth time since last June, and left the door open to
further rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Recent economic reports have offered a mixed report on whether
the Fed's rate increases are successfully slowing the economy, and
the next major report won't hit the market until Thursday, when the
Commerce Department issues a preliminary report on the gross
domestic product during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors led the Dow lower, tumbling 9{ to 77{. The
company is allowing shareholders to swap stock for a tracking stock
in Hughes Electronics, a wholly owned subsidiary of GM. The deal is
ultimately expected to boost GM's stock price, and will reduce the
number of GM shares on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Hughes tracking stock rose 7[ to 97 in active
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 402.34 million
shares, slightly behind Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 17.67 to 462.03.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.8 percent as its
leading technology stocks fell steeply.
</P>
<P>
