<HEADLINE> Justices To Decide Arbitration Role  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether a federal law can be invoked to enforce arbitration
agreements in most labor and employment contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will hear arguments by Circuit City Stores
that an exception within the Federal Arbitration Act is a narrow
one, and therefore the law can be used to enforce most contract
agreements to arbitrate employment disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves lawsuit filed by Saint Clair Adams, who worked
for Circuit City in Santa Rosa, Calif. When he joined the company
in 1995, he was required to sign a document agreeing to arbitrate
''any and all ... claims, disputes or controversies'' related to
his employment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Adams sued Circuit City in California state court,
alleging he had suffered on-the-job harassment because of his
sexual orientation in violation of a state fair-employment law.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City went to federal court, saying the Federal
Arbitration Act required the dispute to be handled through
arbitration rather than a state court lawsuit. A federal judge
agreed, but the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed and let
Adams' lawsuit go forward.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitration law states it does not apply to employment
contracts for ''seamen, railroad employees or any other class of
workers engaged in foreign or interstate commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit court had previously decided that exception
meant the law did not apply to employment or labor contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, Circuit City's lawyers said other
appeals courts have read the exception more narrowly to apply only
to workers actually working in the ''movement of goods in
interstate commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams' lawyers said Circuit City's argument would strip state
courts of their power to decide whether such arbitration agreements
are fair.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Circuit City Stores vs. Adams, 99-1379.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 9th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
