<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio picks up backing of Conservative Party leader  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- In a crucial development for his fledgling
Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton, Rep. Rick Lazio
picked up the backing Monday of state Conservative Party Chairman
Michael Long.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a real race. The difference is there's going
to be a contrast here,'' Long said. ''There's going to be a united
front. Old alliances are going to be working together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Long had earlier refused to get behind the former Republican
standardbearer, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, because of
his support for abortion rights and his closeness to the Liberal
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the boss of the state's Liberal Party came out Monday
''100 percent'' behind the first lady's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no doubt she will emerge as the candidate of the
Liberal Party,'' Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   While no Republican has been elected to statewide office in New
York since 1974 without Conservative Party backing, no Democrat has
been elected governor or U.S. senator in New York without Liberal
Party backing since that party was founded in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
also count votes from third-party ballot lines. That can be
critical in a close race. In 1994, Republican George Pataki beat
three-term Democratic incumbent Mario Cuomo in the governor's race
on the strength of the vote on the Conservative Party line.
</P>
<P>
   Long's support for Lazio came as the Long Island congressman
continued a two-day whirlwind tour of upstate New York designed to
boost his name recognition quickly in a large state where he is
little known.
</P>
<P>
   After stops in Elmira, Watertown and the Utica area, Lazio was
to be joined for an airport rally Monday in Albany by Gov. George
Pataki, his chief political patron, and by state Republican
Chairman William Powers. Lazio visited Buffalo, Rochester, Syracuse
and Binghamton on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It is Pataki who, in the wake of Giuliani's withdrawal from the
Senate race on Friday to concentrate on dealing with his prostate
cancer, has been instrumental in lining up GOP leaders behind
Lazio's resurrected candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Lazio suspended preparations for a Senate run at
Pataki's urging after the governor, under pressure from national
and state GOP leaders, endorsed Giuliani's candidacy. The
congressman fired his campaign machinery up again on Friday,
immediately after Giuliani quit the race.
</P>
<P>
   Harding, meanwhile, has been a top political adviser to Giuliani
and the mayor's withdrawal from the race cleared the way for the
Liberal Party boss to get behind Clinton, as he had been under
pressure to do from party colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative and Liberal party state nominating convention
are being held June 3 at which time their leaders' choices are
expected to be ratified.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign quickly used Long's backing of Lazio to
press a favorite new theme of the first lady's team -- that Lazio is
too conservative for New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given his conservative record, it's not surprising he would
get the Conservative Party nod,'' Clinton campaign spokesman Howard
Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, on the other hand, has been painting Clinton as a
too-liberal Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   While Long said Lazio had some catching up to do with just five
months to go until the election, the Conservative Party leader
predicted the polls would quickly close.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think his chances are really excellent,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   A statwide New York Post/Fox News poll out Sunday had Clinton
leading Lazio, 46 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Long's backing of Lazio came after former U.S. Rep. Joseph
DioGuardi told the party chairman that he would not continue with
his quest for the Conservative Party's Senate nomination. DioGuardi
had entered the fray because of his policy disagreements with
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   DioGuardi said it was clear Lazio was the choice of Republican
and Conservative party leaders for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's in the best position to send Hillary Clinton back to
Arkansas or Washington or wherever she came from ... He's a fine
young man,'' the former congressman from suburban Westchester
County said in endorsing Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Long had refused to get behind Giuliani's Senate bid because of
the New York City mayor's refusal to come out in favor of a ban on
a late-term abortion procedure that critics call ''partial-birth
abortion'' and the mayor's strong ties to the state's Liberal
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, while maintaining he is an abortion rights supporter,
favors banning the abortion procedure and has never run with
Liberal Party backing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 1245 </TRAILER>
