<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riders say service on rail line has improved  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Commuters on Metro-North Railroad's New
Haven Line are happier with their service these days, but still not
as satisfied as riders on the Harlem and Hudson lines, a survey
found.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven Line riders were more satisfied with service in the
first three months of this year than in the previous quarter,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Riders gave higher scores in seven out of eight categories for
the January-to-March period.
</P>
<P>
   The highest rating was on-time performance, which was 7.3, up
from a 6.9 rating in the October-to-December period. The ratings
use a 1-to-10 scale, with 10 being the most satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The only category that went down from last quarter was overall
conditions on trains, which fell from 6.7 to 6.5.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven Line scores have been lower than on the Hudson and
Harlem lines for years. Metro-North officials said the longer
average rides of New Haven Line commuters could be a contributing
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we do poorly on on-time performance, all the categories
tend to suffer due to general unhappiness,'' said Ted Bowen, a
Metro-North customer service official.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather and faulty equipment on Connecticut trains late last
year also contributed to a poor on-time performance, Metro-North
said. Though the scores have improved, commuters tend to take a
longer time to feel better, Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lag between when we improve things like on-time
performance and when commuters say they are satisfied,'' he said.
''Perception and reality aren't always on the same schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   When discussing the scores at the Connecticut Metro
North-Shoreline East Commuter Rail Council's monthly meeting last
week, some commuters complained that the New Haven Line should not
settle for lower quality.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things have been better, and on-time is the big one, but our
riders continue to be less satisfied than the Harlem and Hudson
lines,'' said Rodney Chabot, the council's chairman. ''I hope over
time we see that situation addressed and these scores improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Harris, state Department of Transportation's public
transit bureau chief, told the council to keep the ratings in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ''These scores are still in the seven and eight range,'' Harris
said. ''I can remember years ago when these numbers were fours. So
people are generally satisfied with Metro-North service, with some
bumps along the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 1307 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State AFL-CIO boss asks Connecticut members to boycott blood drives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- With a strike against the state chapter
of the American Red Cross entering its fourth week, the president
of the Connecticut AFL-CIO on Wednesday urged the organization's
265,000 members to boycott blood drives until the dispute is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The strike involves Red Cross workers who collect and deliver
donated blood. The 200 members of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees Local 3145 walked out May 1 when the
old contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their strike is our strike,'' AFL-CIO President John Olsen
said Monday. ''Their struggle is our struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   No negotiations have been held since the second week of the
strike and none were scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still at an impasse,'' said Red Cross spokeswoman Lynn
Townshend.
</P>
<P>
   Townshend said she was disappointed ''that anyone would try to
hinder blood donations in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she said the Red Cross was attempting to stick to its
revised schedule of one blood drive per day. Since the strike
began, Red Cross officials said the average daily blood collection
has dwindled to about 100 pints, down from 600 units a day.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Cross says it can still meet the blood-product
demands of 32 Connecticut hospitals by using blood collected
outside the state and managed by the Red Cross system from St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's blood drive was held at the First Presbyterian
Church in New Canaan, Townshend said. Olsen said he hoped no
AFL-CIO member would take part.
</P>
<P>
   ''This strike is about fairness,'' he said. ''It's about workers
who have every right to improve the quality of their own lives when
they've been improving the quality of all our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is seeking better pay, benefits, scheduling and
retirement packages. Current pay ranges from $10 to $22 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The strikers say the Red Cross receives $1,000 for each pint of
blood it collects, once the blood is broken down into its various
components. Townshend wouldn't say how much the Red Cross makes on
a pint of blood but did say the union's estimate was ''a bit
high.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike marks the second time the union has walked out
against the Red Cross. The first strike, which occurred in 1975
when AFSCME organized the Red Cross, lasted for two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 1416 </TRAILER>
