<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Michael J. Fox Bids Adieu to Show  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In this month of series cliffhangers, ''Spin
City'' presents the most gripping: What will the future hold for
Michael J. Fox?
</P>
<P>
   Fox is leaving the ABC sitcom after Wednesday night's season
finale to fight his case of Parkinson's disease, marking the last,
most poignant stop on the farewell tour he has traveled since he
announced his plans in January.
</P>
<P>
   A farewell tour doesn't have to mean forever, of course. And you
can expect to see Fox on ''Spin City'' in an occasional guest
appearance next season (like during ratings sweeps).
</P>
<P>
   But there is an unequivocal finality to this episode. It is
titled ''Goodbye,'' and signals Fox's exit from the 4-year-old
series that was built around his brash, boyish style.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the March week it was shot ''turned out to be
fairly emotional,'' Fox said. ''I learned how much I love the
people in this show and the verisimilitude there is between my life
and Michael Flaherty's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty is the character Fox plays -- the deputy mayor of New
York who this week takes the fall for a scandal that could sink the
entire city administration. On the plus side, he is carnally
rewarded for his self-sacrifice by Caitlin (Heather Locklear), his
former colleague and new love.
</P>
<P>
   The episode gives Fox an efficient send-off. In return, he
rallies his diminished energies, if all too visibly, for a bravura
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can listen for real-life parallels embedded in the
dialogue:
</P>
<P>
   -- ''I know the system,'' declares Flaherty/Fox. (Political?
Medical?)
</P>
<P>
   -- ''I'll survive this.'' (His professional setback? His
Parkinson's?)
</P>
<P>
   -- ''It's not like it's over, right?''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most affecting cloaked references comes from the
courtly, befuddled Mayor Winston, played by Barry Bostwick.
</P>
<P>
   ''The years that we've been working together, they've been the
best years of my life,'' the mayor tells his deputy. ''Even during
the tough times, I could always count on you.''
</P>
<P>
   This speech rings with truth when you recall that, after ''Spin
City'' premiered in 1996, Bostwick underwent treatment for prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the feelings that pervade this episode for cast and
audience alike are insufficient to raise it above what ''Spin
City'' has been from the start. A series that has never won an Emmy
and currently occupies 41st place in the ratings for the season,
its main distinction has always been the actor it's now losing.
</P>
<P>
   Now the series Fox is leaving behind will leave New York, to
shoot on a Los Angeles sound stage next season. Charlie Sheen will
join the cast.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's finale, Flaherty reflects on his sudden
joblessness.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every morning,'' he says, ''I wake up and I got somewhere to
go, I got something to do. What am I going to do tomorrow when the
alarm goes off?''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Fox knows pretty well what he's going to be
doing for his foreseeable tomorrows. He will devote more time to
his new career as an advocate for research into finding a cure for
Parkinson's, a progressive neurological disorder. The 38-year-old
star says he expects a cure by the time he is 50.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has insisted that he isn't giving up show business. But as
he told Diane Sawyer on ''20/20'' last week, ''it takes a different
degree of energy and concentration for me to do things than for you
to do things.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that as an actor with Parkinson's disease playing
someone who doesn't have Parkinson's, he is consumed with ''doing
the math on how to physically navigate my way through a scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ''As a performer,'' he said, ''I want people to see what I'm
performing, not the dexterity and gymnastics it was taking for me
to perform it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 1518 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Reviews Guare's 'Lydie Breeze'  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- From playwright John Guare, who gave us ''The
House of Blue Leaves'' and ''Six Degrees of Separation,'' one would
expect better than the long and tedious ''Lydie Breeze,'' his new
off-Broadway production at the New York Theater Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   It's really two plays, each 2{ hours long. The first is
subtitled ''Bulfinch's Mythology.'' The second, ''The Sacredness of
the Next Task,'' has more tangents than a trigonometry lesson.
Guare apparently intended to fashion Greek tragedy into a modern
family saga, but he has failed to make his people interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The first play begins with Lydie Breeze (Elizabeth Marvel), a
nurse, arriving on Nantucket Island in 1875 to start a utopian
community with three men she chose from Civil War hospitals. One of
them, Joshua Hickman (Bill Camp), she marries; the second, Amos
Mason (Boris McGiver), is a laborer; the third, Dan Grady (Matt
Servitto), is a railroad worker who comes home with money he took
from a dead man on a train. Lydie Breeze falls in love with him.
</P>
<P>
   The second act is set in the print shop in a Boston prison where
Hickman is serving time for murdering Grady. Mason, having gone to
Harvard law school and become a lawyer with political aspirations,
visits Hickman to dissuade him from publishing his book about the
utopian experiment.
</P>
<P>
   In the second play, set on Nantucket in 1895, there are three
suicides, a ghost, a rape combined with mistaken identity, several
cases of syphilis, and some laughs, possibly unintended. And yet
for all the action and plot trajectories, it rarely gets
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Grady's actor son Jeremiah (Jefferson Mays) returns to spout
some monologues from his role as Frankenstein's monster. Lydie
Breeze's two daughters appear, in unfortunate circumstances. Each
is saved by a man who appears at the last minute -- Alexandra Oliver
by Christopher McCann, playing an inventor, and Alicia Goranson by
Thomas Shaw, playing a bird bander.
</P>
<P>
   A bird bander is someone who puts bands on birds to track them
and measure far they fly. Played by Shaw, it's the production's one
appealing role, but it's a small one, near the end, and is hardly
worth waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Itamar Kubovy directed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 1521 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
