<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls to Low for the Year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index continued its steady
decline today, falling nearly 150 points as investors sold
technology stocks on fears that earnings will be hurt by rising
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq was down 144.35 at 3,246.05. With the decline, the Nasdaq
has wiped out virtually all the spectacular gains it piled on from
early November until March 10, when it peaked at 5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have decided that their exuberance for high-tech and
Internet stocks -- which gave the Nasdaq an unprecedented 86 percent
gain last year -- was either unjustified or premature, given the
upward trend in interest rates, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in the Nasdaq spread throughout the market today.
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 189.16 at 10,437.69,
having clawed back from a loss of more than 250 points. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 24.39 at 1,382.56.
</P>
<P>
   Bellwether technology companies were continuing a long, steady
slide that has knocked the Nasdaq composite index 37 percent below
its March 10 record close of 5,048.62. Intel fell 3~ to 114 and
Cisco Systems fell 1] to 52 1/16. Oracle fell 5{ to 64 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors have determined that with interest rates
on the rise, the high price of technology stocks may not be
justified by their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the correction for technology stocks still has
further to go,'' said Thomas McManus, equity portfolio strategist
at Banc of America Securities in New York. Even the bellwether
names, which attracted investors in the wake of April's technology
selloff, are now under escalating pressure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had suggested that investors increase the quality and
liquidity of tech stock holdings in anticipation of a sharp
correction, but the risk remains that technology blue-chips become
increasingly overvalued and overowned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts are holding to the view that the current weakness
is washing out the exuberance that dominated the market at the
close of 1999 and in early 2000. But with the damage mounting,
investors are struggling to determine which technology stocks -- if
any -- are worthy of their still-high prices.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said many of the Internet retailers and other fledgling
companies that racked up steep stock prices at the height of the
technology boom may never recover. More established companies,
however, remain solid investments and are becoming relative
bargains in the continuing tech washout.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fundamentals of the technology sector are still there,''
said Michael K. Farr, president of investment counselors Farr,
Miller &AMP; Washington in Washington, D.C. ''But no longer will being
a 'dot com' get you a following. You have to have strong, growing
earnings and a clear business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's greatest obstacle remains rising interest
rates, analysts said. Last week, the Federal Reserve raised rates
for the sixth time since last June, and left the door open to
further rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Recent economic reports have offered a mixed report on whether
the Fed's rate increases are successfully slowing the economy, and
the next major report won't hit the market until Thursday, when the
Commerce Department issues a preliminary report on the gross
domestic product during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors led the Dow lower, tumbling 8~ to 78[. The
company is allowing shareholders to swap stock for a tracking stock
in Hughes Electronics, a wholly owned subsidiary of GM. The deal is
ultimately expected to boost GM's stock price, and will reduce the
number of GM shares on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Hughes tracking stock rose 6 9/16 to 96 7/16 in
active trading.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 663.84 million
shares, slightly behind Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively light volume was a clear contrast to the waves of
selling that dragged the Nasdaq lower in April. Analysts said there
was no sign of panic in the market. Yet many believe that it would
take a high-volume, full-bore selloff to drive the Nasdaq to a
level that would attract bargain hunters and allow the index to
rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 16.61 to
463.09.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.8 percent as its
leading technology stocks fell steeply.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
