<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted War Criminal Testifies  </HEADLINE>
By ANTHONY DEUTSCH
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- A convicted Bosnian war criminal
who admitted murdering Muslims in the Bosnian war testified Monday
against his former commander, Serb Gen. Radislav Krstic.
</P>
<P>
   Drazen Erdemovic told the U.N. tribunal said he saw Bosnian Serb
military police ordering Muslims off buses at the execution site --
the Branjevo farm in the protected U.N. enclave of Srebrenica in
July 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the (Muslim) men turned their backs to us, we were
ordered to shoot. ... There were between 1,000 and 1,200 of them,''
Erdemovic testified.
</P>
<P>
   Erdemovic, 28, was sentenced in March 1998 to five years
imprisonment after pleading guilty to taking part in the Srebrenica
executions.
</P>
<P>
   He returned voluntarily to testify in Krstic's genocide trial
after serving two years in pretrial custody and a shortened
sentence in a Norwegian jail. He is now in the tribunal's protected
witness program; the date of his release was not given.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces broke through U.N. defenses at the so-called ''safe
haven'' of Srebrenica on July 11, 1995. In the next week they
slaughtered at least 7,500 Muslim men and boys, prosecutors say.
Krstic is accused of leading the army's Drina Corps, which
allegedly carried out the bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said I didn't want to do it,'' said Erdemovic, a Bosnian
Croat married to a Serb woman who first fought with Muslim forces.
He says he was forced to join the Bosnian Serb army or face
expulsion from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   If he hadn't participated in the murders at Branjevo farm, a
military agricultural settlement, Erdemovic said he would have had
to ''stand up with them'' and be shot alongside the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were terrible moments,'' Erdemovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Krstic's trial reopened Monday after a five-week recess.
Testimony in coming weeks will focus on the Serb command structure
during the massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Krstic, 52, has pleaded innocent to charges of genocide, war
crimes, crimes against humanity and grave breaches of the Geneva
Conventions. He could spend the rest of his life in prison if found
guilty of any single charge.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal was established seven years ago by the U.N.
Security Council to prosecute those responsible for atrocities in
the Balkans following the disintegration of Yugoslavia in 1991. It
has sentenced 14 Serb, Muslim and Croat defendants to prison terms
of up to 45 years. The tribunal has no death penalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
