<HEADLINE> Norwegian Delegation in Sri Lanka  </HEADLINE>
By KRISHNAN GURUSWAMY
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- The Sri Lankan army and air force
attacked Tamil rebel positions on Monday even as a Norwegian
delegation met Sri Lanka's foreign minister to try to broker a
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Deputy Foreign Minister Raymond Johansen held talks
with Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar hours after flying to
Colombo, the capital, on a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   A government statement said more than 150 rebels were killed in
fighting that raged Sunday and Monday for control of the key
northern peninsula of Jaffna. It said the bodies of 68 guerrillas
were recovered in the battlefields in Chavakachcheri, a strategic
region east of Jaffna city, the former rebel capital.
</P>
<P>
   Independent confirmation was not possible since journalists are
not allowed into the war zone and news about the battle is
censored.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombo, Kadirgamar and Johansen shook hands and posed for
photographers at the start of a closed-door meeting. Johansen was
accompanied by Erik Solheim, Oslo's special envoy to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   Johansen later met President Chandrika Kumaratunga to try to
find ways to end the 17-year-old war that has killed more than
62,000 people in the Indian Ocean nation off India.
</P>
<P>
   Solheim, who visited neighboring India last week as part of
Norway's peace initiative, reportedly is in touch with leaders of
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam through the rebels' London
office.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, home of the Nobel Peace Prize, has frequently used
backdoor diplomacy to resolve some of the world's most difficult
conflicts. Norwegian diplomats helped mediate the 1993 peace accord
between Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Former Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek visited Sri
Lanka in February after Kumaratunga sought Oslo's help in resuming
talks with the rebels after a five-year suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have claimed several battle successes in recent
weeks. The government says it has deployed modern weapons to
contain the rebel threat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a police officer who crushed India's Sikh uprising
arrived in Colombo to advise Sri Lanka's government on fighting the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   K.P.S. Gill, who retired as chief of police in India's northern
Punjab state, is expected to work with Sri Lankan police and
military officials to draw up a strategy to counter the Tamil Tiger
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Tamil political parties urged both the government and the rebels
on Monday to agree to a cease-fire to help the peace negotiators
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time is ripe for the hostilities to end and start talks,''
said Douglas Devananda of the Eelam Peoples Democratic Party, a
former rebel group that has renounced violence and joined the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas have been fighting for a separate homeland for
Tamils since 1983, accusing the majority Sinhalese of widespread
discrimination in education and jobs. The Sinhalese control the
government and the military.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
