<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Blocks Some Air Bag Lawsuits  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court says millions of Americans
who drive or ride in cars built before federal regulations required
air bags cannot, if they get hurt in accidents, sue automakers for
not installing the safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   Voting 5-4 Monday, the court said federal regulation of
automobile safety pre-empts, or blocks, lawsuits in which people
invoke state product-liability laws and contend air bags could have
saved them from harm.
</P>
<P>
   The decision killed the lawsuit of a District of Columbia woman
who suffered serious head injuries when she crashed her 1987 Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ''The basic question ... is whether a common-law 'no air bag'
action like the one before us actually conflicts with (federal
regulation),'' Justice Stephen B. Breyer wrote for the court. ''We
hold that it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in September 1989, carmakers had to protect the driver
with ''either an air bag or automatic seat belt.'' A lengthy
phase-in period followed, and cars made since September 1997 must
have air bags for the driver and front-seat passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis Geier's Honda Accord had a seat belt and shoulder
harness, which she was wearing, when in 1992 her car went out of
control on a curve and struck a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Her 1995 lawsuit said the car was defective because it did not
have a driver's side air bag even though federal regulations did
not require one when the car was manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   American Honda Motor Co. successfully fought off Geier's lawsuit
in lower courts by arguing that a federal law and regulation shield
it from liability. The Supreme Court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision focused narrowly on air bag technology and
regulation, and did not appear to carry immediate impact for
lawsuits over other alleged defects.
</P>
<P>
   The air bag issue had split lower courts. Five of them and the
highest courts of two states -- Pennsylvania and Mississippi -- had
barred such lawsuits. But the highest courts in five states -- New
Hampshire, Indiana, Arizona, Ohio and New York -- had allowed them.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Breyer to form the court's slender majority were Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Clarence Thomas and
Ruth Bader Ginsburg dissented.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For Geier v. American Honda Motor Co., 98-1811:
http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/ Click on ''this month's
decisions'' or http://www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
