<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Reviews 'Swan Lake'  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Every ''Swan Lake,'' it seems, is open to
interpretation. Rudolf Nureyev sat himself down in a chair, went to
sleep and dreamed the whole thing. The New York City Ballet's
version, a year ago, stressed the formal over the romantic.
Broadway's 1998 version featured an all-male cast.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Kevin McKenzie's production for American Ballet
Theater, in which two men dance Rothbart, giving a whole new
dimension to the evil magician in Tchaikovsky's masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   This ''Swan Lake,'' beautifully danced and costumed, had its
premiere March 24 at Kennedy Center and was danced for the first
time in New York Friday night at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie keeps much of the 1895 production as it was
choreographed by Marius Petipa and Lev Ivanov. He adds a prologue,
which choreographer Vladimir Bourmeister did in Moscow in 1953, in
which Rothbart captures Odette and turns her into a swan.
</P>
<P>
   In his prologue, Odette (Susan Jaffe) is seen through a
translucent curtain being grabbed and carried away by a large,
ungainly man (Brian Reeder). He is one Rothbart; the other is a
dazzling dancer (Vladimir Malakhov).
</P>
<P>
   In Act 3, when the Black Swan tricks the prince into thinking
she's the swan he loves, Malakhov's solos nearly steal the show.
The prince, danced by Jose Manuel Carreno, dances splendidly, his
jumps high and clean. But whenever Malakhov's Rothbart is seen,
he's doing something spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe is a very special Odette, able to make her arms ripple.
When, as a swan, she first meets the prince, her movements show
fright. As she comes to love and trust him, she is like an
unfolding flower.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie has modified the fouettes -- whipping turns -- which are
in the original choreography and are too fast for most ballerinas.
The costumes are sumptuous in the Act 1 scene of the prince's
birthday party, where his mother (Georgina Parkinson) tells him he
must marry, and in Act 3 in ball, where he is to choose a bride.
Yan Chen, Sandra Brown and Herman Cornejo danc an exceptionally
fine pas de trois in Act 1.
</P>
<P>
   In Act 2, where the prince meets Odette by the lake, McKenzie
arranges the excellent corps de ballet of swans differently from
the usual.
</P>
<P>
   Endings of ''Swan Lake'' vary, from Rothbart dying and melting
down to the lovers riding across the sky in what looks like Santa's
sleigh. McKenzie has devised a new ending, in which first Odette
and then the prince dive from a high rock into the lake. It's a
hugely dramatic finale, after which the couple's resurrection
inside a large rising moon is almost anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   Ermanno Florio conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 1620 </TRAILER>
