<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lobbying on MTBE bill before Pataki intensifies  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Lobbying over a bill to ban MTBE, a gasoline
additive intended to reduce air pollution but blamed for
contaminating water supplies, has been intense in the days before
Gov. George Pataki decides whether to sign the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's office on Monday had no comment on the bill approved by
both houses of the Legislature. He has until Wednesday to sign or
veto the bill. The governor has said he prefers a federal approach
to the MTBE -- or methyl tertiary butyl ether -- problem, but is
''taking a look'' at the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''MTBE has become one of the most prominent contaminants in
groundwater and surface waters in New York and across the nation,''
Sarah Meyland, the Citizen's Campaign for the Environment's
executive director, said in a statement. A ban would ''set an
important example for other states ... and ultimately, this will
force the federal government to address the issue,'' Meyland
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The American Lung Association and a coalition of other states'
environmental officials, on the other hand, are pushing to let the
federal government handle the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know our position makes us as popular as a skunk at an
environmentalists' garden party,'' said Peter Iwanowicz, director
of environmental health for the American Lung Association's New
York chapter. However, he said that the current bill plays into the
interests of producers of ethanol, which is made from corn.
</P>
<P>
   Both MTBE and ethanol make gasoline burn cleaner by adding
oxygen to it. But ethanol also has drawbacks -- it can erode ozone.
</P>
<P>
   The American Lung Association says that banning MTBE without
other safeguards would ''present an unacceptable risk of increased
air pollution.'' The lung association also said that if Congress
doesn't act, a phase out in New York may be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast States for Coordinated Air Use Management, which
includes officials from Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New
Hampshire, New Jersey, Rhode Island and Vermont, is also opposed to
the bill before Pataki. ''It is unnecessary and unacceptable to
improve water quality at the cost of undermining clean air and
public health,'' the group said in a statement. That group also
said the use of ethanol in the summer would increase air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Citizens Campaign for the Environment on Monday
displayed the names of 25,000 residents who support a ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see no downside to signing this bill,'' said Robert Foster,
legislative director of Citizens Campaign for the Environment. ''My
understanding is (MTBE) is not as effective as intended. The clean
air benefits are not that well documented.'' Foster also suggested
that not banning MTBE would essentially be yielding to the oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE is used in one-third of gasoline sold in the United States,
primarily in areas with smog problems. It has leaked in areas
across New York state but Long Island has been a noted trouble
spot. Several counties in and around New York City are required to
use such oxygenated gas.
</P>
<P>
   A European study in the mid-1990s linked MTBE to liver and
kidney tumors in mice. The danger to humans is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   California -- the nation's No. 1 user of MTBE -- has banned MTBE
by the end of 2002. An Environmental Protection Agency panel has
recommended strengthening programs to reduce MTBE's presence in
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Department of Environmental Conservation has listed
about 1,700 MTBE spills around the state, although not all the
spills have contaminated water supplies. The DEC did not
immediately comment on its recommendation to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, New York's legislation would go into effect Jan. 1,
2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 1627 </TRAILER>
