<HEADLINE> AM-CT--Red Cross Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,400  </HEADLINE>
State AFL-CIO boss asks Connecticut members to boycott blood
drives   
sdhofonrh
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- With a strike against the state chapter
of the American Red Cross entering its fourth week, the president
of the Connecticut AFL-CIO on Monday urged the organization's
265,000 members to boycott blood drives until the dispute is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The strike involves Red Cross workers who collect and deliver
donated blood. The 200 members of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees Local 3145 walked out May 1 when the
old contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their strike is our strike,'' AFL-CIO President John Olsen
said Monday. ''Their struggle is our struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   No talks have been held since the second week of the strike, but
negotiations were scheduled to resume at 1 p.m. on Thursday at a
site yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still at an impasse,'' said Red Cross spokeswoman Lynn
Townshend.
</P>
<P>
   Townshend said she was disappointed ''that anyone would try to
hinder blood donations in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she said the Red Cross was attempting to stick to its
revised schedule of one blood drive per day. Since the strike
began, Red Cross officials said the average daily blood collection
has dwindled to about 100 pints, down from 600 units a day.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Cross says it can still meet the blood-product
demands of 32 Connecticut hospitals by using blood collected
outside the state and managed by the Red Cross system from St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's blood drive was held at the First Presbyterian
Church in New Canaan, Townshend said. Olsen said he hoped no
AFL-CIO member would take part.
</P>
<P>
   ''This strike is about fairness,'' he said. ''It's about workers
who have every right to improve the quality of their own lives when
they've been improving the quality of all our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is seeking better pay, benefits, scheduling and
retirement packages. Current pay ranges from $10 to $22 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The strikers say the Red Cross receives $1,000 for each pint of
blood it collects, once the blood is broken down into its various
components. Townshend wouldn't say how much the Red Cross makes on
a pint of blood but did say the union's estimate was ''a bit
high.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike marks the second time the union has walked out
against the Red Cross. The first strike, which occurred in 1975
when AFSCME organized the Red Cross, lasted for two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 1635 </TRAILER>
