<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Calls for Filmmaker Park Fees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill passed by the House Monday could
require moviemakers, television producers, and professional
photographers to pay more to work in national parks and
federally-owned lands.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, passed by a voice vote authorizes the
secretaries of Interior and Agriculture to set fees for the
commercial use of public land and use the money from those fees to
pay for land management and permit processing costs. It now goes to
the White House for the president's signature.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the fee would be determined by the number of
people using site and the duration of filming.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate amended the bill in November to ban commercial
land-use that threatens environmental damage, public safety or
impedes the general public from using the park.
</P>
<P>
   ''If permitting filming allows us to recoup its cost and to deal
with some of the other needs of our land management agency then
that is a desired result,'' said bill sponsor Rep. Joel Hefley,
R-Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Hefley said the bill had the support of the Interior Department
and the Motion Picture Association of America, whose president,
Jack Valenti, said it was ''common-sense legislation that benefits
our national parks and all those who visit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Television news, newsreels, and some commercial photography
would be exempt from the fees.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers paid to shoot movies in national parks until 1948
when the Interior Department prohibited future collection of
location fees in national parks and wildlife refuges.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 154
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
