<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Promise Seen for Spinal Injuries  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL RECER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A nerve tissue that is usually damaged in
spinal injuries was restored in laboratory animals using embryonic
stem cells -- a study that may eventually lead to a new treatment
for people paralyzed by injury or disease.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Washington University in St. Louis School of
Medicine showed in mouse and rat studies that embryonic stem cells
can be used in adult animals to regrow tissue, called myelin, that
covers and insulates nerve fibers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John W. McDonald, lead author of the study, said that the
loss of function from spinal injury and disease is often because of
damaged or eroded myelin. When this insulating tissue is gone,
axons, or nerve fibers, stop sending signals to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Demyelination is a central feature of most central nervous
system injuries,'' said McDonald. ''Regaining myelination can offer
substantial improvement in function.''
</P>
<P>
   A report on the study appears Tuesday in the Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   In their study, Washington University researchers used embryonic
stem cells from mice to regrow myelin tissue in the spinal cords of
rats.
</P>
<P>
   Embryonic stem cells, or ES cells, are master cells formed early
in development. The cells can transform into any type of cell in
the body.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers used chemicals to cause the mouse ES cells to turn
into a culture containing the precursors of neurons, astrocytes and
oligodendrocytes -- the key cells in the nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said that his group found that in rats with injured
spines injections of these cultures caused oligodendrocytes to move
to the injury site and to tightly cover the exposed nerve fibers
with new myelin.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first demonstration that oligodendrocytes from
embryonic stem cells can remyelinate the injured adult nervous
system,'' said McDonald. This is significant, he noted, because
injuries and disease that cause the loss of myelin occur most
frequently in adults.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, said McDonald, is to test if growing new myelin
will allow animals with spinal injuries to regain the functions,
such as bladder control or leg movement, that was lost to the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said that his lab was ready to test this technique in
humans, but that current regulations prevent labs receiving federal
research funds from using human embryonic stem cells in research.
</P>
<P>
   ''Essentially we are blocked from working with human embryonic
stem cells,'' he said. ''This has been a big hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   Using human embryonic stem cells in research is controversial
because the cells must originate from a human embryo or fetus that
is aborted. The National Institutes of Health last year published
proposed guidelines that would permit some federally funded
research with human ES cells, but the final guidelines are still
under review, an NIH spokesman said. Some members of Congress have
said they would oppose the use of human ES cells in research.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's research site:
http://www.neuro.wustl.edu/people/mcdonald.htm
</P>
<P>
   Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences site:
http://intl.pnas.org/icons/home/pnaslogo--home.gif
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 1701 </TRAILER>
