<DOCNO> APW20000522.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonior Takes On Clinton Over China  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On the day Bill Clinton welcomed former
presidents and Cabinet officers to the White House to endorse China
trade legislation, Rep. David Bonior appeared with an actress,
Goldie Hawn, in the Capitol to argue the opposing side.
</P>
<P>
   And on the morning after a key committee gave unexpectedly
lopsided approval to the bill, the Michigan Democrat stood outside
with Chinese dissidents, just as he stood with union workers,
environmentalists, veterans and other opponents on other days.
</P>
<P>
   He may be outvoted in the end by a powerful lobbying effort by
the White House and business, as some lawmakers on both sides of
the issue predict. But Bonior, the No. 2 Democrat in the House with
close ties to organized labor, remains undeterred in his role as
point man for the opposition on a measure that would make trading
rules with China permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I care deeply about labor rights and the environment. I've
built my whole career around these principles, and human rights,''
he said in an interview in his office on the third floor of the
Capitol. ''... If they can be peeled back, eroded through trade
agreements, then I see a betrayal of the values of the people that
went before me.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, he says, he means his grandmother, ''who marched as a
suffragette to give women the right to vote,'' and his grandfather
''in the sit-down strikes at the (auto) plants'' in the 1930s fight
for labor rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior, 54, won election to Congress from an area around those
auto plants in 1976, after service in the Air Force, experience as
an adoption caseworker and probation officer and four years in the
Michigan Legislature. His voting record is reliably liberal on
economic and many social issues. A Catholic, he opposes abortion
rights, unusual for a man who has risen so high in national
Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Since Republicans gained a majority in the 1994 elections,
Bonior has been a fierce critic of GOP economic policies and former
Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing trade legislation is nothing new for him. He fought the
North American Free Trade Agreement that passed Congress in 1993,
arguing it would export American jobs to Mexico, where labor and
environmental protections were, in his view, inadequate. And he
voted against Chinese trade privileges in a series of annual votes
in recent years on numerous grounds, including human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The current China measure, which comes to a vote this week,
would end such yearly votes and give China so-called normalized
trading rules permanently. Bonior says that would end any chance of
influencing Chinese policy.
</P>
<P>
   This time there's a difference in the political equation.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case with NAFTA, the House Democratic leader, Rep.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri, opposes the China bill. But Democrats
say he is now more focused on his party's efforts to win the House
this fall, and working to prevent any serious splits in a caucus
divided over the trade measure.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he avoids public events that Bonior's office arranges --
the very appearances that are a routine part of Gephardt's effort
to promote Democratic legislation such as a minimum wage increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't drop everything else that I do here to work on one
issue,'' Gephardt told reporters recently. ''I have a wide-ranging
job that encompasses a lot of issues and a lot of activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior, too, recognizes potential political fallout from a vote
on which organized labor has invested so much. Passage of the North
American Free Trade Agreement helped contribute to a falloff in
votes in the 1994 election that cost Democrats their majority.
</P>
<P>
   But, he adds, ''It's not clear yet whether this will have the
same impact that NAFTA did'' if it passes.
</P>
<P>
   Allies and opponents alike credit Bonior's work.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's representing a majority of the Democratic caucus and his
constituency (in Michigan). That's his job,'' said Rep. Jim Moran,
a Virginia Democrat who supports the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bonior's the only one (among top Democrats) who's being
straight on this,'' says Rep. Tom Davis, a member of the GOP
leadership who accuses Gephardt of ''gaming'' the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like him or not, he's effective,'' added Davis, the head of
the GOP campaign committee, which tried but failed to field a
candidate capable of mounting a strong challenge to Bonior in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and most House Republicans are expected to vote for the
trade bill, along with as many as a third of all Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonior, soft-spoken in his office, says they have it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have the policy of the past masquerading as the future,''
he said. ''That's not good enough because what's at stake here is
the standard of living, the quality of air and water and all of the
other important human rights issues we've been raising.
</P>
<P>
   ''So this is kind of central to why I got involved in government
in the first place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
