<HEADLINE> 3 Iran Jews Enter Innocent Spy Plea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran (AP) -- Many of their co-defendants have admitted
guilt, but three of 13 Iranian Jews accused of spying for Israel
said Monday they will plead innocent to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The three men spoke to reporters before their hearing began in
the southern Iranian city of Shiraz. They said they had not hired
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't need lawyers. We are not spies. We are innocent and
we will be acquitted, God willing,'' shoe merchant Omid Tefilin
said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his co-defendants at Monday's hearing, student Navid
Balazadeh and shopkeeper Nejatollah Brukhimnejad, have been free on
bail since February, apparently because the charges against them
are less serious than those against the other 10 defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The other 10 are in custody. Of those, eight have pleaded
guilty, while one, Farzad Kashi, has denied the charges. The tenth
said he collected information for Israel, but it did not amount to
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has denied that any of the defendants were its spies.
</P>
<P>
   The trial has generated international concern, and the defense
has questioned the fairness of the closed-door revolutionary court
where the judge is also the prosecutor and there is no jury. The
trial is closed to the public because it involves issues of
national security.
</P>
<P>
   The main defendants have been accused of collecting photographs
of military installations for Israel, collecting information for
sabotage operations and studying ways to poison the water supply of
Shiraz. Iranian state television has broadcast the confessions of
two defendants, who said they were trained and paid by Israel to
gather secrets in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have said they would insist on seeing evidence
that secret information was handed to Israel. They have said the
indictments so far do not carry the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for espionage here is a long prison term. The death
penalty would apply only to charges of ''moharebeh'' -- fighting
against God and the state. The men have not been charged with that
offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
