<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Set Congo Pullout  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwandan and Ugandan army commanders agreed
to start withdrawing troops and heavy weapons this week from the
northern Congo city of Kisangani, which they will turn over to U.N.
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   At a late-night meeting Sunday, Ugandan army chief Maj. Gen.
Jeje Odongo and Rwandan army chief-of-staff Brig. Gen. Kayumba
Nyamwasa signed an agreement to begin a 16-day withdrawal on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the agreement, the two armies will withdraw to at
least 60 miles from Kisangani, each leaving behind 216 soldiers to
jointly patrol until 1,000 U.N. observers and troops take charge.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda -- nominal allies in a 1{-year war against
Congolese President Laurent Kabila -- failed to resolve whether the
Rwandan-backed Congolese rebels should also withdraw from the city.
The rebels have objected to leaving, arguing that only foreigners
should withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very sincere about what we've discussed,'' Odongo told
reporters, but he added that the rebels' presence in Kisangani was
''essential'' for the success of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda support rival rebel groups in Congo. The two
countries poured troops and arms into supporting the rebels, after
accusing Kabila training their enemies -- Rwandan Hutu militiamen,
who carried out the 1994 genocide in Rwanda, and Sudan-backed
Ugandan rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But quarrels among army officers and differences over war
conduct led the Ugandan and Rwandan troops to fight each other in
Kisangani, first in August and again this month when the Ugandans
tried to add troops from northern Congo and expel Rwandans from the
city, Rwandan army and U.N. military observers said.
</P>
<P>
   A team of U.N. military observers witnessed the signing of
Monday's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has promised to send 5,537 U.N. observers and
troops to four locations in Congo, including Kisangani, to
strengthen a fragile cease-fire and oversee the withdrawal of
foreign troops and disarming of militias.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment, which is not expected before July, is part of a
peace agreement signed in August by Kabila and the rebels. Rwanda
and Uganda also signed, as did Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, which
back Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations who
helped draft the plan to demilitarize Kisangani, said this week
that the Kisangani deployment should be given priority to keep
fighting from flaring up again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
