<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Refugees Flood Sudan  </HEADLINE>
By MOHAMED OSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL-LAFA CAMP, Sudan (AP) -- Weakened by its own civil war and
poverty, Sudan struggled Monday to cope with an influx of refugees
fleeing violence in neighboring Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan -- which for 30 years has been receiving Eritrean refugees
fleeing warfare and drought -- had hoped to begin sending Eritreans
home Tuesday. But intensified fighting between Eritrea and Ethiopia
has prompted a new refugee exodus, forcing Sudan to put its plans
on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Yalssa Yamani returned to her home in Eritrea
from the Sudanese refugee camp el-Lafa, only to find herself back
this week with her husband and 3-month-old baby.
</P>
<P>
   ''What can we do?'' she said. ''If we go home, which we want to
do, we will get killed. And if we stay here, we will repeat the
story of those who lived here for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamani's family waited four days at el-Lafa -- Sudan's largest
camp -- to register as refugees, which entitles them to a share of
scant resources, food and other aid.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees live out in the open on the semi-desert terrain,
hiding from the scorching sun under strips of cloth hung from
sticks or behind carts they use to carry their belongings. The
Sudanese government had not yet brought tents.
</P>
<P>
   Daytime temperatures topped 100 degrees at the camp, near the
border town of Kassala, about 250 miles east of Khartoum. Local aid
groups provided vaccinations against infectious disease and basic
medical care on Monday, including treatment for dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. World Food Program brought in cooking oil, wheat flour
and beans that was distributed Monday by the state refugee office.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan borders both Eritrea and Ethiopia, two of the poorest
countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   About 25,000 Eritrean refugees have registered in Kassala, and
the number was expected to rise to 200,000, Kassala Gov. Ibrahim
Mahmoud Hamid said. The Sudanese refugees were among at least
550,000 Eritreans that have been uprooted by the latest fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia invaded Eritrea on May 12, resuming the violence that
has cost the lives of tens of thousands of soldiers and civilians
since first erupting in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian forces seized the western town of Barentu, 75 miles
east of Kassala. Ethiopia also claimed to have taken territory 60
miles from the Eritrean capital, Asmara.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid said some 70 Eritrean soldiers had crossed into Sudan and
turned in their weapons, ''but we are sure some of those refugees
are actually soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Hamid said his government would do all it could for the
refugees, he acknowledged that some Sudanese would be reluctant to
help.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan has accused Eritrea of supporting Sudanese opposition
groups who have attacked Sudan from inside Eritrea. In March,
southern Sudanese rebels and northern opposition groups based in
Eritrea seized Sudan's Hamashkoraib district near Kassala.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have people who lost loved ones during shelling of our
borders, you have others who lost their limbs as a result of land
mines planted by the opposition coming from inside Eritrea,'' Hamid
said. ''People here are not unlikely to have some hard feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's civil war and attendant famines have killed nearly 2
million people since 1983. Sudanese rebels seek autonomy for the
predominantly Christian and animist south from the Muslim-dominated
north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
