<HEADLINE> Limbaugh Auditioned For MNF Show  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rush Limbaugh confirmed Monday he auditioned
for ''Monday Night Football,'' and he thinks the result was
''excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative talk show host said he recently traveled to Los
Angeles and called a prerecorded game with play-by-play host Al
Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was excellent, to tell you the truth,'' Limbaugh
said in an interview with WMAL-AM.
</P>
<P>
   ''I surprised myself. I had not seen the game we did. And I
didn't try to study up on the game, because who knows how the real
game's going to play out, you never know,'' he added. ''So the
thing that I came away with after it was over was how much I really
dug it. It was even more fun than I thought it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Monday Night Football,'' though still one of the most popular
shows on television, has suffered a modest ratings decline in
recent years. Analyst Boomer Esiason was fired in March, and Don
Ohlmeyer, the show's producer in the 1970s, was brought back to
revive the spice the broadcast had in the days of Howard Cosell and
Don Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh has lobbied on his radio show for the chance to
audition. But the thought of the outspoken and often polarizing
personality moving to the broadcast booth has been ridiculed by
some.
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh said he wouldn't try to be another Cosell, and he began
discussing the lineup of games this season as someone who is ready
to take the job.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look at the Monday night schedule this season,'' Limbaugh
said. ''I hate to say this, but if the Rams or Redskins don't
perform up to potential, the schedule is going to come back to
haunt them. So, I played this out and have been very serious about
it all along, and there have been discussions about whether or not
I can handle this and do a Monday radio show at the same time.
There is no question that I could.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC would not comment on Limbaugh's audition, or even confirm
that it actually took place.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not comment on any individual,'' spokesman Mark Mandel
said. ''We will wait until we make our formal announcement in early
June.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
