<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians' Baez Promoted To Double-A  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cuban pitcher Danys Baez, signed this winter to
a $14 million contract by Cleveland, was promoted to Double-A Akron
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians are being forced to make all kinds of moves because
of injuries to pitchers. Baez was a candidate to become Cleveland's
No. 5 starter during spring training, but began the year at Kinston
(A) of the Carolina League as the Indians chose to take their time
in developing the right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, Baez went 2-2 with a 4.71 ERA in nine
outings for Kinston. In his last two starts, the 22-year-old was
1-0 with a 0.71 ERA and had 16 strikeouts in 12 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians won a bidding war with several teams, including the
Atlanta Braves, and signed Baez last November. Cleveland committed
itself to a pitcher it barely knew and one it had mostly scouted on
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Baez, who defected while playing for the Cuban national team
during the 1999 Pan Am Games in Winnipeg, struggled during training
camp while trying to adjust to his new life in the United States
and a new lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Once a $10 per month pitcher in Cuba, he was suddenly a
multimillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   In spring training, the 225-pound Baez's fastball rarely reached
90 mph and the curveball that made hitters' knees buckle on film
wasn't as sharp. He hadn't pitched for nearly seven months since
defecting just before the Aug. 1 gold-medal game in Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   Baez will make his debut for the Aeros at home Wednesday night
against New Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians wanted Baez to enjoy some success before bringing
him up through their system this season. However, injuries to
starters Jaret Wright and Charles Nagy and reliever Ricardo Rincon
has Cleveland making moves much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Baez's promotion is likely to be followed on Tuesday with the
promotion of right-hander Tim Drew from Akron to start Wednesday
night's game against the Detroit Tigers. It would be Drew's major
league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, the Indians' No. 1 pick in 1997, is 3-2 with a 2.42 ERA at
Akron. The 21-year-old younger brother of St. Louis outfielder J.D.
Drew is just one of a number of young pitching prospects the
Indians are counting on.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, 24-year-old Paul Rigdon made his big league debut
with the Indians and pitched seven shutout innings to beat the New
York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland made several other pitching moves Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Lorraine, released by the Chicago Cubs on May 11, was
signed to a minor-league contract and assigned to Triple-A Buffalo.
The 27-year-old lefty went 1-2 with a 6.47 ERA in eight games for
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians also announced that Chad Ogea, who won two games in
the 1997 World Series for them, was placed on the 15-day disabled
list at Buffalo. Ogea was released by Tampa Bay on April 12 before
being signed by the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Ogea has elbow problems and is returning to Cleveland to be
examined. He lasted just 1 1-3 innings in his only start for the
Bisons.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Indians acquired right-hander Richie Lewis, 34, from
the New York Mets for a player to be named. Lewis was 3-4 with a
3.21 ERA in nine starts for Triple-A Norfolk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
