<HEADLINE> Corzine on the trial in Trenton wins city mayor's endorsement  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine hit the
capital city Monday, winning the mayor's backing and greeting
elderly residents at a once-derelict train station now in use as a
health and social center in one of the city's most depressed
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is running against former Gov. Jim Florio, who had no
public campaign events Monday. Corzine began the day addressing a
postal-workers' union meeting in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's appearances yielded a friendly response from Trenton's
poor elderly, most of them black and Hispanic, and most of them
unaware of who Corzine is. He briefly discussed his plan to expand
Medicare to include prescription drug coverage, but generally spent
his time in casual handshakes and small talk.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a friendly response from Mayor Douglas Palmer, a
Democrat who runs for office here in nonpartisan elections and thus
has remained somewhat aloof from partisan politics, allowing him to
shift easily into alliances with Republicans in control of his
city's main industry: state government.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said he valued Palmer's backing, especially because of
this independence.
</P>
<P>
   ''He doesn't make endorsements on a regular basis,'' Corzine
said. ''We have spent a bunch of time together to talk about things
that I think we can do together, and I think he feels comfortable
that I am sincere about what I am going try to get accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer praised Corzine for addressing immunization and
children's health, job training and abandoned factory sites.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to have the things that I want, I can't sit on the
sidelines,'' Palmer said. ''That is why it is very critical not
only for myself but for Trenton and New Jersey to get behind a man
like Jon Corzine, who has bold initiatives, who is not part of the
old regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio spokesman Jim Lanard said the former governor was
attending closed campaign events Monday, and he had no comment on
the Palmer endorsement.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
