<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Milosevic Group To Register  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In an attempt to stave off a
possible ban, a popular, pro-democracy student group ostracized by
Slobodan Milosevic's government announced Monday it will try to
register as an official organization.
</P>
<P>
   The group Otpor, which means Resistance, is known for its street
protests mocking Milosevic's autocratic rule. It has rapidly gained
popularity among opposition-minded Serbs who are fed up with
bickering among leaders of opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, Otpor has been blamed for the slaying
of a top official of Milosevic's ruling party and targeted by
police and the government as ''a terrorist group, fascists and
traitors.'' Dozens of its student activists have been arrested or
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to ease the pressure, the group announced Monday
it would try to register with the federal Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ... want to show that brutal force and intimidation cannot
suppress a democratic movement,'' said Branko Ilic, an Otpor
activist.
</P>
<P>
   A number of university professors, more than 50 members of the
Academy of Science, actors, musicians and other public figures
turned up Monday to sign Otpor's founding act, which is to be
submitted to the ministry for registration later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Several police officers monitored the founding ceremony at
Belgrade's independent Media Center. No arrests were made, but
earlier Monday a group of young men dressed in black and shouting
''Traitors'' and ''Fascists,'' interrupted another Otpor gathering
at Belgrade's University.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Milosevic's government cracked down on Belgrade's
main independent media, seizing the opposition-run Studio B
television and popular B2-92 radio station. The government proposed
a restrictive ''anti-terrorist'' law, which would allow it to ban
opposition parties and groups and arrest their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe accused Yugoslav Information Minister Goran Matic of
threatening one of the group's representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-nation OSCE said in a statement that Matic sent Freimut
Duve, the group's representative on media freedom, a letter
accusing Duve of being an ''accomplice in a crime'' by urging the
government to stop cracking down on the independent media.
</P>
<P>
   ''Support for independent media is defined as 'terrorism and a
crime against a sovereign state,''' Matic said, according to the
OSCE statement.
</P>
<P>
   The OSCE said it called on Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic to
clarify whether he personally supported Matic's views.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders announced another major anti-government rally
for Saturday titled ''For Serbia, without terror and fear - for
freedom of Studio B and other media.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, leader of the Serbian Renewal Movement, the
single largest opposition party, told reporters that ''complete
media darkness reigned'' in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, the Yugoslav Foreign Ministry
protested Sunday to the European Union over a ban on trade and
finance between most EU member countries and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A senior European official said that international sanctions
against the Belgrade regime would remain as long as the Yugoslav
president rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, the Pact has a vacant seat for Serbia, the Pact waits
for Serbia to join, ... when things change,'' said Bodo Hombach,
coordinator of the Stability Pact for Southeast Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
