<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman high court nominee clears first confirmation test  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman's sixth nominee to
the state Supreme Court cleared his first legislative hurdle Monday
without a word of opposition from lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   James R. Zazzali's appointment now goes to the full state
Senate, after an unanimous vote to approve his nomination by the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   If ultimately confirmed, Zazzali would replace Associate Justice
Daniel O'Hern, who reaches the mandatory retirement age of 70 on
May 23.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat, Zazzali served as an assistant prosecutor when
former Gov. Brendan Byrne was the Essex County prosecutor. As
governor, Byrne later named Zazzali his attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne told the Senate panel that a former president of a state
lawyers association called Zazzali the finest appointment yet by
Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would certainly say that Jim Zazzali fits that bill,'' Byrne
said. ''All I can say is I'm proud of him. You should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Byrne was retired Associate Justice Stewart G. Pollock,
a Republican who said Zazzali works across party and ideological
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''You may never have an easier decision than the one you have
before you today,'' Pollock said.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali faced only brief questioning from senators on issues
including the role of the judiciary and the needs of the court
system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I keenly believe the Legislature is the voice of the people,
and the judges and the justices should recognize that,'' Zazzali
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali served as attorney general for 10 months at the end of
former Gov. Brendan Byrne's term in 1981 and 1982. He also served
as general counsel to the New Jersey Sports and Exposition
Authority under Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali, who turns 63 on June 17, is the oldest person Whitman
has nominated. While all Supreme Court justices must be confirmed
for lifetime tenure by the Senate after seven years, this will not
be an issue for Zazzali since he will hit mandatory retirement in
2007.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the chief justice, the six associate justices are
supposed to be evenly split, three Republicans and three Democrats.
Since O'Hern is a Democrat, tradition holds that he be replaced
with someone from the same party.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali was a commissioner on the State Commission of
Investigation from 1984 to 1994, including a period as chairman.
The SCI is an independent office created by the Legislature to
examine and issue written reports on corruption and policy
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman last year named Zazzali to a search committee to find
candidates for State Police superintendent. He also headed a
coalition of six former state attorneys general who supported
former Attorney General Peter Verniero's hotly contested nomination
to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali, of Rumson, is a partner in the Newark law firm Zazzali,
Zazzali, Fagella &AMP; Nowak with his brother, Andrew Zazzali. He
graduated from Georgetown University in 1958 and earned a law
degree there in 1962.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
