<HEADLINE> S.C. Gets NCAA Tournament Top Seed  </HEADLINE>
By DENNIS WASZAK Jr.
<TEXT>
<P>
   South Carolina was selected the top seed and five other
Southeastern Conference teams were included in the 64-team Division
I college baseball tournament field announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Gamecocks (52-8), ranked No. 1 in national polls for most of
the season, will play Liberty on Friday in the first round of the
double-elimination tournament which leads to the College World
Series in Omaha, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't wait to see South Carolina play,'' said Dick Rockwell,
chairman of the NCAA selection committee. ''Any team that wins 50
games, I would think would have to be the favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   The other seeded teams include Louisiana State (43-17), Georgia
Tech (47-14), Clemson (45-16), Houston (44-15), Florida State
(45-15), Arizona State (42-13) and Stanford (42-13).
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, Auburn, Florida and Mississippi State received
automatic bids to join South Carolina and LSU as SEC teams in the
tournament. The Atlantic Coast Conference and Big 12 each have five
teams in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said the committee puts most of its focus on strength
of conference and strength of non-conference schedules when
selecting at-large teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no one I feel we left out of this tournament,''
Rockwell said, adding that the committee spent 11 hours Sunday and
2{ more Monday preparing the brackets ''The parity pleases us. The
new teams please us. What we're hearing already from the sites
about attendance pleases us. And when you look at the possibility
of the super-regional matchups, we really have the makings of some
real exciting baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to South Carolina, the other regional hosts are
Arizona State, Baylor, Cal State-Fullerton, Clemson, Florida State,
Georgia Tech, Houston, Louisiana-Lafayette, Louisiana State, Miami,
Minnesota, Mississippi State, Oklahoma, Rutgers and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The Fullerton, Calif., regional with Cal State-Fullerton,
Southern California, Loyola Marymount and Virginia Tech, and the
Oklahoma City regional with UCLA, Oklahoma, Oral Roberts and
Delaware are expected to be among the most competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (37-17-1) makes its 28th consecutive tournament appearance
to extend its NCAA record and will try to join Texas (1949 and
'50), USC (1970-74), Stanford (1987-88) and LSU (1996-97) as the
only repeat champions.
</P>
<P>
   There are 26 schools in this year's field that didn't play in
the tournament last year, three of which are making their first
NCAA tournament appearances: Army (24-18-1), Butler (31-26) and
Wagner (24-28-1). The Seahawks, who won the Northeast Conference
tournament, are one of three schools in the tournament with a
losing record. Southwestern Athletic Conference tournament champion
Jackson State (26-28) and Sun Belt winner South Alabama (27-31) are
also in.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose State (36-20) is making its first tournament appearance
since 1971, while Penn State (41-16) is making its first since
1976.
</P>
<P>
   While schools like Oklahoma State, not in the tournament for the
first time since 1981, Pepperdine and Georgia were considered but
ultimately left out of the tournament field, Rockwell said the
committee is pleased with its decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel a lot better about the field this year than I did last
year at this time,'' Rockwell said. ''We had a group of about
seven, eight or nine teams that we considered, but there wasn't
really a 65th team.''
</P>
<P>
   The regionals are played on campus fields, except for Rutgers
and Oklahoma. The Rutgers regional will be played at Yogi Berra
Stadium in Upper Montclair, N.J., and the Oklahoma regional will be
played at Bricktown Ballpark in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   The winners of each regional advance to one of eight
best-of-three super regionals on June 2. The super-regional winners
advance to the College World Series in Omaha, Neb., which starts
June 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
