<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Seeks US, UN Aid in Pullout  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Israel's security belt inside southern
Lebanon collapsed Monday, Prime Minister Ehud Barak sought the help
of the United States and the United Nations for a peaceful pullout
of Israeli troops this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright responded with telephone
calls to Arab leaders and a statement saying ''there can be no
justification for initiating acts of violence'' while Israel was
carrying out a withdrawal called for by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by satellite to a conference of the most influential
pro-Israel lobby in the United States, Barak said he would hold
Syria and Lebanon accountable if the withdrawal was marked by
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Barak squeezed in the speech to 2,000 members of the American
Israeli Public Affairs Committee amid hurried telephone
consultation with Albright and senior Israeli military officers.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, meanwhile, consulted by telephone with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and leaders of Lebanon, Syria, Egypt
and Saudi Arabia, as well as with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   She then called on all parties ''to exercise maximum restraint
and refrain from any acts of violence.'' She also urged support for
Annan as he tries to minimize civilian casualties and help
stabilize the region.
</P>
<P>
   With the situation along the border with Lebanon growing more
tense by the day, Barak said Albright had assured him the United
States would play a role in the pullout -- one that he did not spell
out -- and that he wanted the U.N. Security Council to endorse the
withdrawal as well.
</P>
<P>
   Albright has expressed support for Barak's decision, but has not
said whether the United States would provide concrete help.
Meanwhile, the administration is calliing on other governments to
endorse the pullout and wants it carried out through the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   As Barak spoke, Israeli-allied militiamen, who could be treated
harshly for helping Israel to maintain the security zone for 22
years, fled in panic toward Israel's border. Hundreds of Lebanese
civilians rushed forward to fill the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which wields effective control over Lebanon, wants any
Israeli pullout accompanied by surrender of the Golan Heights, the
strategic plateau it lost in the 1967 Mideast war. But unable to
come to terms with Syria, Barak intends to get Israeli troops out
of Lebanon rather than take more casualties at the hands of
militant guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are determined to pull out in the near future,'' Barak
said. ''I would not recommend to anyone to try us once we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the pullout has already begun in bits and pieces.
Barak may be positioning himself to complete it before a
self-imposed July 7 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, his warning to Lebanon and Syria was unqualified.
''We hold the Lebanese and Syrian governments responsible to make
sure it will be quiet,'' the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told American Israeli Public Affairs Committee members
that a quarter-million Israelis in northern villages were compelled
to take refuge in shelters from cross-border attacks. ''They may
have to stay there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said confidently, ''We will prevail and we will pull out
of Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak had been scheduled to attend the conference and probably
to meet with President Clinton at the White House, but the violence
in southern Lebanon and on the West Bank caused him to cancel the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tensions, U.S. mediator Dennis B. Ross assured the
pro-Israel group that Israel and the Arabs ''have come a long way''
toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no question there is a promise of success,'' Ross
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the American official, who shuttled between Washington and
the Middle East for talks with Israel and Palestinian leaders and
also participated in secret negotiations in Stockholm, Sweden, said
agreements cannot be reached with violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
