<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver survives leadership vote by fellow Democrats  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver
survived a challenge to his job Monday, but not before nearly three
hours of public criticism from fellow Democrats about how he runs
the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal to change the rules to allow an immediate vote on
Silver's speakership failed 63-85, or by 13 votes in the 149-member
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise that the challenge launched by the former
Democratic majority leader, Michael Bragman, failed. He
acknowledged Monday morning he did not have the votes to supplant
Silver among Democrats in the chamber and instead would turn his
campaign to become speaker into an effort to reform the rules of
the house.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 19 Assembly Democrats voted to suspend the rules.
They were joined by 44 minority Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The vote represented the remnants of a six-day-long rebellion by
Bragman which began spreading by rumors and word of mouth during
last Tuesday's Democratic state convention in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Bragman announced he had a ''rock-solid'' core
of Democrats -- at one point he said it was 53 -- who favored him
over Silver as new speaker. That number would have been enough to
make Bragman the new speaker in a closed vote among the 98 Assembly
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Bragman conceded that number shrunk among what he called
''bludgeoning'' and ''threatening'' by Silver and the speaker's
allies since last week.
</P>
<P>
   There were only 19 Democrats willing to stand with Bragman at a
news conference Monday in which he said he was forming a Democratic
Majority Reform Caucus to promote reform in the operation of the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Following his defeat on the floor, Bragman insisted, ''The
speaker is fatally wounded'' and said his Democrat-led group will
eventually prove to be the speaker's undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Silver scheduled a news conference Tuesday to discuss the
leadership fight.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's vote followed an extraordinary display of disaffection
by more than a dozen Democrats in a chamber where Democrats rarely
air unhappiness with leaders publicly.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic 15-minute address before a jammed and tense
chamber, Bragman accused Silver of letting lobbyists and
non-elected staff members control legislation instead of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has been listening for years to members complain
about how hard it is to even see Silver face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   He contended the conference committees by which small portions
of the last three state budgets were negotiated have been shams
controlled by legislative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman even said, ''It is wrong to treat the members from the
minority side with such disrespect.'' Republicans in the Assembly --
like Democrats in the Republican-dominated state Senate -- have
essentially no input on legislation and usually cannot even ''sign
on'' to Democratic bills as sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about my personal ambition,'' Bragman said. ''It
could not have been with some many involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, stripped of his majority leader's job and perks when he
went public last week with his challenge against Silver, received a
standing ovation from the 51 Republicans in the Assembly and from
his Democratic allies while the other Democrats sat silent.
</P>
<P>
   Silver allies fired back.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard Brodsky of Westchester County said the
resolution before the Assembly Monday ''isn't the vehicle'' and
Bragman ''isn't the man'' to correct the complaints being voiced
against Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ''The notion that unreturned phone calls or inappropriate staff
acts -- which will happen, under anyone -- are grounds for
impeachment, is ludicrous,'' Brodsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Clarence Norman, the Brooklyn Democratic leader and
the deputy majority leader, said the Bragman forces ''failed
miserably'' to meet their burden of proving why Silver should not
remain speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''I say you change leadership when institutions are paralyzed
with corruption or blatant incompetency,'' said Norman, rumored to
be one of Bragman's possible successors, ''and certainly no one can
say our Speaker Sheldon Silver is incompetent or corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Assemblyman Arthur Eve, a Silver backer who was first
elected in 1966, urged the dissidents to back down and work with
Silver to resolve their problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't destroy this institution,'' he pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   A close Silver partisan, Assemblyman Herman Farrell of
Manhattan, predicted that Republicans would use the disharmony
among Assembly Democrats among the party's candidates this
November.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't find the words here to make it go away,'' Farrell
said. ''It needs to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bragman ally, Martin Luster of Tompkins County, was one of two
insurgents so far to be penalized by Silver. Both he and Ronald
Tocci of Westchester County lost their committee chairmanships and
$12,500-a-year stipends for joining Bragman's team.
</P>
<P>
   Luster said he is a ''big boy'' and understands there are
penalties to pay for being on the wrong side of a coup against a
political leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I am not willing to accept the notion that with our vote
today that this house is in good order, that we run it as a
democratic institution,'' Luster said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bragman before him, Luster said he was at ease because he
feels he can speak his mind about how the Assembly is run.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never felt as liberated as I do as this moment,''
Luster said. ''I have never felt so sure of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, from suburban Syracuse, and the Manhattanite Silver had
maintained an uneasy alliance in the Assembly since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said Silver threatened to run many members with
Democratic primary opponents this year or to redistrict them out of
office in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot be angry because I know what you went through,''
Bragman told his Democratic colleagues Monday. ''I think you for
hanging on as long as you could.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 1908 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
