<DOCNO> APW20000522.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FEC Battle Delays Judge Nominees  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Federal Election Commission nominee's views
on campaign finance law and Democrats' desire to debate them
extensively continued to hold up Senate action Monday on more than
70 of President Clinton's nominees for federal judgeships and
administration jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless we can get an agreement to have some debate time and a
vote sewn up ..., then 72 nominations are in jeopardy,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott said shortly after recessing a
deadlocked Senate early in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, R-Miss., and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.,
had agreed to holding a vote on FEC nominee Bradley A. Smith, who
is opposed by several Democrats, in exchange for getting several
federal judicial nominees through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   However, Democrats who want to put new restrictions on who can
contribute to political campaigns and how much objected to the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senate confirmation of Brad Smith could affect the
administration of the federal election laws for years to come,''
Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., said Friday. ''I objected ...
because I felt that the majority was acting too hastily. The
proposal contemplated too little debate and a vote occurring too
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle and Lott had agreed to allow senators to hold a debate
on Smith for more than 10 hours, then a debate on a couple of the
judges and then approve a block of non-controversial nominees,
including most of the judges. The more controversial nominees like
Smith would be voted on separately.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats say Smith is an unacceptable choice for the
FEC because of his belief that government should not limit the size
of campaign contributions. At his confirmation hearing, Smith told
senators that he would enforce campaign law as it is rather than as
he wishes it would be but that assurance failed to placate his
foes.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who teaches at Capital University Law School in Columbus,
Ohio, said he feels confident of his chances if he gets a vote. ''I
think everybody agrees a majority of the Senate would vote to
confirm me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been the bargaining chip for Democrats to get some of
President Clinton's judicial nominations through the
Republican-controlled Senate. Republicans, looking to regain the
White House next November after eight years of Clinton's
presidency, have done little this year to expedite approval of
Clinton's nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ''We basically offered up to 72 nominations, including 16
judges, and all that's required is a vote on a couple of FEC
nominations and a couple of judges,'' Lott said. ''If the Democrats
object to a package like this, it doesn't look like they want to
get any more nominations done this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The 72 nominations include positions at the State, Justice and
Treasury departments and seats on the Harry Truman Scholarship
Foundation and even the Metropolitan Washington Airports Authority.
Until they can get all of the nominations cleared, everything was
''pretty much'' stuck, Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven judges have been approved by the Senate this year. In
addition to the 16 on the Senate floor calendar are another 36 are
awaiting approval by the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Renit Schmelzer, a spokeswoman for Daschle, D-S.D., said the
holdup is ''senators on our side wanting the debate to happen on
Wednesday and Thursday when everybody was here and could hear them
and stuff. Lott wanted the debate to happen today. That's what it's
bogged down over.''
</P>
<P>
   Many senators do not return to the capital from their home
states on Mondays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
