<HEADLINE> Four Republican hopefuls to crowd the stage for cable TV debate  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDISON, N.J. (AP) -- The four candidates for the Republican
nomination for U.S. Senate are scheduled to appear
shoulder-to-shoulder for a live debate on cable television Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second time U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-New Providence;
state Sen. William Gormley, R-Atlantic; Essex County executive Jim
Treffinger; and Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin will appear
before TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   But the confrontation has taken on greater importance as the
first of three debates this week, capped by an appearance on ABC-TV
network stations for all four of them this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The primary is June 6. The contest has been somewhat
overshadowed thus far by the Democratic primary between the
high-spending Jon Corzine and former Gov. Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Franks and Gormley are seen as the leaders of the pack based on
support from within the ranks of the Republican Party, although the
few polls taken suggest all of them are close and are virtually
unknown to voters. Treffinger has a formidable base of support in
Essex and Passaic counties, and has joined the two leaders in
raising more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   While the three GOP campaigns try to dismiss Sabrin, who until
recently was a Libertarian, few outside observers are willing to do
so because of his appeal to anti-abortion and antigun control
elements of the party that can be quite active at primary time.
Franks, Gormley and Treffinger all fashion themselves as GOP
moderates, supporting abortion rights with restrictions and
proposing more clamps on gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   The four sparred early in the campaign on May 8 in a debate
televised on the New Jersey Network public television station.
Monday's debate is being hosted by News 12 New Jersey, a cable TV
news channel.
</P>
<P>
   As at the NJN forum, the News 12 debate will confine the large
group of candidates to answering reporters' questions within set
time limits, which may restrict how much they are able to attack
one another or provide vivid contrasts to their platforms in a
50-minute time frame.
</P>
</TEXT>
