<DOCNO> APW20000522.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Megan's mother testifies as sex offender amendment advances  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The mother of a girl raped and killed in
1994 by a convicted sex offender who lived across the street says
parents want information about such offenders posted on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Kanka told the Senate Judiciary Committee on Monday that
parents with whom she has spoken support a change to the state
constitution so they can have Internet access to sex offender
information.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee and an Assembly committee on
Monday passed bills proposing the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say if this becomes law, New Jersey would be the
first state in the country with a constitutional guarantee to view
lists of molesters online.
</P>
<P>
   Kanka, whose daughter, Megan, was raped and killed in 1994 by a
sex offender who lived across the street from her Mercer County
home, told the Senate Judiciary Committee that, six years ago she
expected it would be easy to alert parents to the dangers of repeat
sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was quite a simple thing to us,'' she said. But what
eventually became Megan's Law has been hampered by court
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Parents need the information to protect their children, Kanka
said. But as the law stands now, only parents who live in the same
neighborhood where sex offenders who are classified as dangerous
live get those details, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having Internet access will be able to alert parents to look
beyond their streets,'' Kanka said.
</P>
<P>
   In her talks with parents, Kanka said many would gladly vote to
approve any amendment that would give them more information.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'd like to see better access,'' Kanka said.
</P>
<P>
   The public notifications now allowed by Megan's Law are on hold
while the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reviews the law.
Without the amendment, any plan to post the sex offender
information on the Internet would likely be struck down by the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shouldn't need a constitutional amendment to protect these
children but we do,'' said Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco,
R-Union, one of the bill sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco said New Jersey is far behind other states that
allow much of the same sex offender details on Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   The only opposition came from the state chapter of the American
Civil Liberties Union and lawyer John J. Furlong, who represented
the sex offender in the first state Supreme Court case challenging
Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   Furlong told the senators they are free to post all criminal
convictions online now. But he also said they are just as free to
sponsor group therapy sessions for offenders to help treat the
underlying causes of the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's cheap,'' Furlong said, ''and it works.''
</P>
<P>
   His suggestions elicited no comment from the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman offered both houses of the Legislature the
amendment on March 27. She also submitted legislation directing the
superintendent of the State Police to prepare the Internet
registry.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee voted 8-0 to forward the bill.
The version in the Assembly cleared the Law and Public Safety
Committee by a vote of 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills now will be considered by each house. No public
hearing dates have been scheduled. If passed by the Legislature,
the amendment would be put to voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   For those sex offenders labeled a minimal risk, the amendment
would let the public submit a person's name and one other piece of
information, such as his home address, to see the Internet registry
about him.
</P>
<P>
   For those considered at moderate or high risk of re-offending,
the public simply would have to access the Internet registry. The
registry would contain the offender's name and aliases, any Megan's
Law offenses committed, his age, race, date of birth, height,
weight, hair and eye color, address and a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, for those considered at least risk, prosecutors tell
police departments that the offender is living in the community.
For those perceived to be at moderate or high risk of reoffending,
the law allows prosecutors to provide an offender's name, address
and photo to residents, schools and day care centers in a carefully
defined area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 1946 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Dinosaur' Devours Competition  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HARRIGAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Stories don't get much older than
''Dinosaur,'' but audiences for the new Disney animated movie
didn't mind, sending it to the top of the weekend box office with
$38.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Using computer animation to depict the twilight years of the
biggest animals to roam Earth, ''Dinosaur'' had nearly double the
take of second-place ''Gladiator,'' which had led the way during
its first two weeks in North American theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The top 12 films grossed $102.5 million, up slightly from the
same weekend last year, when 1999's biggest movie, ''Star Wars:
Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' opened. Estimates on Sunday had
indicated weekend business would finish down slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The top 20 movies at North American theaters Friday through
Sunday, followed by distribution studio, gross, number of theater
locations, average receipts per location, total gross and number of
weeks in release, as compiled Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co.
Inc.:
</P>
<P>
   1. ''Dinosaur,'' Disney, $38.9 million, 3,257 locations, $11,930
average, $38.9 million, one week.
</P>
<P>
   2. ''Gladiator,'' DreamWorks, $19.7 million, 3,041 locations,
$6,494 average, $103.1 million, three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   3. ''Road Trip,'' DreamWorks, $15.5 million, 2,530 locations,
$6,120 average, $15.5 million, one week.
</P>
<P>
   4. ''U-571,'' Universal, $4.6 million, 2,736 locations, $1,695
average, $64.4 million, five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   5. ''Frequency,'' New Line, $4.3 million, 2,202 locations,
$1,971 average, $30.4 million, four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   6. ''Battlefield Earth,'' Warner Bros., $3.92 million, 3,307
locations, $1,187 average, $18.3 million, two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   7. ''Small Time Crooks,'' DreamWorks, $3.88 million, 865
locations, $4,486 average, $3.88 million, one week.
</P>
<P>
   8. ''Center Stage,'' Sony, $3.3 million, 1,506 locations, $2,160
average, $9.1 million, two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   9. ''Where the Heart Is,'' Fox, $2.8 million, 2,147 locations,
$1,291 average, $25.6 million, four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   10. ''The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas,'' Universal, $2.5
million, 2,692 locations, $945 average, $27.8 million, four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   11. ''Screwed,'' Universal, $1.7 million, 1,761 locations, $980
average, $6 million, two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   12. ''Love and Basketball,'' New Line, $1.3 million, 833
locations, $1,603 average, $24.1 million, five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   13. ''Rules of Engagement,'' Paramount, $1.2 million, 1,062
locations, $1,096 average, $58.4 million, seven weeks.
</P>
