<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six partners with Pyramid Cos. sue Robert Congel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Six partners of mall magnate Robert Congel
are accusing the Pyramid Cos. founder of defrauding them of more
than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in federal court Monday, the plaintiffs
allege that Congel shifted funds between mall partnerships without
the authority to do so, said attorney Michael Endler.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Pyramid Cos. malls are owned by different investors
who have partnered with Congel, Endler said. The plaintiffs are
partners in 10 of the Pyramid malls in New York and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a number of years, Bob Congel and a close-knit group of
insiders have essentially been operating all of these partnerships
as if they were sole owners,'' Endler said. The plaintiffs believe
that the shifting of funds was not authorized in their agreements
and was done in a manner to defraud the partners, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Pyramid Cos., said the allegations are false and
were made by partners who were upset when various Pyramid
properties failed to be sold two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We learned about the filing of this action late in the
afternoon. It was brought about by a handful of partners who have
become inactive in the affairs of their partnerships over the past
several years,'' Pyramid Cos., officials said in a written
statement. ''Collectively they owe their partners a great deal of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The partners suing Congel are John Bersani of Weston, Ma., John
Charters of Needham, Ma., Daniel Lugosch III of Dover, Ma., Peter
Steingraber of Boston, Edward Kellogg of Poughkeepsie, and Robert
Ungerer of Loudonville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Pyramid Cos., based in Syracuse, owns two dozen malls in New
York, Massachusetts and Vermont. Congel recently announced plans to
triple the size of the Carousel Center in Syracuse and make it the
largest mall in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
