<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly panel approves new funding for charter schools  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- State lawmakers took a first step Monday
toward fixing inequities in the way charter schools are funded.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Education Committee passed a bill that would
provide about $10 million more in state aid to fund charter
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The state also would have to do a speedier evaluation of these
experimental schools to resolve broader -- and more expensive --
issues, under the measure, A-1344.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard Bagger, R-Union, agreed to hold the most
costly provision of the original version of the bill -- a phase-out
of state funding to districts that lose students to charter
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than grapple with that issue, which would eventually cost
the state an estimated $37 million, Bagger said he wanted to
quickly address two funding inequities that have emerged recently.
</P>
<P>
   The first is due to a recent ruling from the New Jersey Council
on Local Mandates, which reviews state laws to make sure they do
not put a financial strain on districts and local government.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling struck down state regulations that said districts
must give charter schools 90 percent of what they actually spend on
education.
</P>
<P>
   Under previous state rules, districts could send charter schools
90 percent of what the state says it costs to provide a ''thorough
and efficient education,'' or what a district actually spends --
whichever was lower. The ''T&AMP;E'' amount is usually much lower than
real costs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the state changed that and said districts must pay the
full cost. The council last week said the state can't force
districts to pay the higher amount.
</P>
<P>
   That would have meant a $6 million loss to charter schools, with
cuts ranging from $32 per pupil at the Oceanside Charter School in
Atlantic City to about $3,600 per student at the Red Bank Charter
School in Monmouth County, according to state figures.
</P>
<P>
   That would have crippled some schools, said Sarah Tantillo,
executive director of the New Jersey Charter Public Schools
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bagger's bill, the state would make up the difference
between the T&AMP;E amount and the real costs.
</P>
<P>
   The second fix would funnel $3.8 million through districts to
charter schools for students who transfer from private and
parochial schools, another district or a home-schooled setting into
charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, those students are not counted in their
enrollments and so districts do not receive state aid for them.
</P>
<P>
   But, once they transfer into a charter school, a district
actually loses aid for students it never educated -- or got state
money for.
</P>
<P>
   That problem corrects itself in the second year because once the
students are in charter schools, they are counted and the state
provides aid for them.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would provide money for that first year of lost
funding.
</P>
<P>
   The original version of the legislation would have added a
phase-out provision to charter school funding.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the funding follows the student. So, when a district
loses a child to a charter school, it also loses the state aid for
that student all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Bagger's initial proposal would have phased out that aid, with
the state paying both the charter school and the district for a
portion of students' education in the first three years that the
student transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Districts officials maintain that even though they are no longer
teaching those students who transfer to charter schools, their
costs don't decrease right away.
</P>
<P>
   It takes losing a lot of students, rather than a handful, to
reach an economy of scale where they can consolidate classrooms and
fire teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But Bagger said when he learned the provision would cost an
estimated $37 million in the 2002-2003 school year, he was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   So he decided the issue should be addressed in the evaluation,
which would be due Feb. 1, 2001, rather than Jan. 2002, under the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner David Hespe objected to the shortened
time frame for the evaluation, which would reveal how well charter
schools are performing and what impact they are having on
traditional schools.
</P>
<P>
   He said he needs more time to gather the relevant information.
Bagger said he would work with the department on the timing of the
study.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools were created by the Legislature in 1995 to give
parents a free alternative if they are dissatisfied with their
district's public schools. Charter schools operate with public
funds, but outside many of the rules that govern traditional
schools.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has 46 charter schools that educate about 9,000
students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 2014 </TRAILER>
