<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Rips Clinton on Israel  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush accused the Clinton
administration on Monday of taking sides in last year's Israeli
elections, continuing a pattern of the United States trying ''to
make Israel conform to its own plans and timetables.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Vice President Al Gore, Bush's Democratic rival
for the presidency, called the allegation ''irresponsible and
reckless'' and said it raised questions about Bush's fitness to be
a world leader.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who cited no specifics to support his accusation, said
pressure from the administration on Israel ''is not the path to
peace.'' Instead, the Republican said, the Jewish state should be
supported as it settles its own affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the national election, the administration was seen as
favoring the eventual winner, Ehud Barak, over then-Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu. Among other things, James Carville, President
Clinton's former political adviser, filled that same role for
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said the Texas governor also was
upset that Clinton pressed for settlement deadlines during the 1998
Wye River peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   With the talks faltering, Clinton held lengthy meetings with
both sides on Maryland's Eastern Shore. He also joined Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in setting deadlines this year for
a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''America should not interfere in Israel's democratic process,
and America will not interfere in Israeli elections when I am the
president,'' Bush told some 2,000 delegates attending the annual
policy conference of the American Israel Public Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''In recent times, Washington has tried to make Israel conform
to its own plans and timetables, but this is not the path to
peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his remarks, Bush reiterated his support for moving the
U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ''As soon as I take office, I will begin the process of moving
the U.S. ambassador to the city Israel has chosen as its capital,''
he said to a standing ovation, his only one of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Gore were eager to comment even before the Texas
governor made his statement about Israel's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's irresponsible and reckless for the governor to make such
a charge involving a region of the world where people ought to be
careful what they're saying,'' said Chris Lehane. ''It really does
raise a question of his readiness to be a leader in international
affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech kicked off a week of defense- and national
security-related activity by the governor. On Tuesday, Bush
scheduled a news conference at the National Press Club on defense
and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, speaking at a fund-raiser Monday night, said he
would talk about ensuring ''certainty in an uncertain world'' -- a
phrase he has used when speaking about strengthing the U.S.
military and about making foreign policy priorities so the armed
forces aren't overly deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was introduced by his sister, Doro, at the event, expected
to raise $350,000 to $400,000. And he was surprised by his father,
former President Bush, who snuck into a private reception to shake
his son's hand and pose for a photo. The president happened to be
staying in the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been criticized as inexperienced in foreign
affairs, had also been scheduled to meet with Barak on Tuesday, but
the prime minister canceled his trip after violence flared on
Israel's West Bank and in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bush has met with Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov. On Thursday, he
is to meet in Austin, Texas, with the president of South Africa,
Thabo Mbeki. Mbeki met with Gore on Monday in Washington before
attending a state dinner with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1951, AIPAC is a Jewish lobbying group dedicated to
support for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The group is a potent political fund-raiser, and presidential
and congressional candidates often pay heed to its desires. Gore
was to address the group on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had been scheduled to deliver the keynote address Monday
night before he canceled. Instead he spoke by satellite to a
luncheon and praised AIPAC's support for Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 2039 </TRAILER>
