<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harding: I Still Love Ex-Boyfriend  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM McCALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Fresh out of jail for throwing a hubcap at
her boyfriend and punching him, Tonya Harding says she still loves
him and wants to get back together -- a prospect he may avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The former champion figure skater was released Sunday from jail
in neighboring Clark County, Wash., after serving three days for
her conviction on a disorderly conduct charge.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Harding is to begin 10 days of community service --
also part of her sentence -- by showing up at Camas Cemetery to help
work crews do some sprucing up for Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   Harding will be performing other kinds of community service as
well, according to the police department in Camas, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Harding, 29, pleaded guilty last Thursday in Camas-Washougal
Municipal Court to hurling a hubcap at her boyfriend's head and
then punching him in the face last February.
</P>
<P>
   In some brief remarks released by her manager, Harding said her
conviction and her jail time had been ''a very stressful experience
for everyone involved.''
</P>
<P>
   She repeated an apology to her family and friends, and to her
boyfriend, Darren Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want you all to know that I still love Darren very much,''
Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   But Silver, 28, didn't seem to be in a forgiving mood.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the tabloid TV show ''Inside Edition,''
Silver said Harding had attacked him after they'd been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ''She blindsided me out of the blue,'' said Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was in shock. She hurt my pride more than my face,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Silver said he wished her well: ''I just want her to be
happy and not harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding's manager, Linda Lewis, said she had received more than
1,000 e-mail messages of support for Harding since the conviction
last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Figure Skating Association banned Harding for life and
stripped her of the national title she won in 1994 after Harding's
ex-husband carried out a plot to injure rival skater Nancy Kerrigan
at the U.S. championship in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Harding pleaded guilty in 1994 to Oregon charges of hindering
prosecution but avoided jail time. She was fined $110,000 and
ordered to perform 500 hours of community service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 2043 </TRAILER>
