<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
John Fitzgerald:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- John Fitzgerald, the former Las Vegas Hilton
president who played a key role in the transformation of the city's
gambling industry, died Sunday after a long illness. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald took the helm of the hotel in 1972 after it was
purchased by hotel magnate Barron Hilton. The hotel was originally
the International Hotel and was at one time the largest in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald worked for Hilton in New York and Beverly Hills,
Calif. He instituted stringent cost controls and vigorous marketing
efforts aimed at conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas Hilton became known as a destination for high
rollers and a major convention hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald also served as president of the Nevada Resort
Association and was a member of the Las Vegas Convention and
Visitors Authority's board of directors.
Roy Jackson:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Roy Jackson, a former executive director of the
International North Pacific Fisheries Commission and deputy
director of the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization,
died Thursday of a burst aortic aneurysm. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was a leading force in restoring sockeye and pink salmon
runs throughout the Fraser River system in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   From 1938 to 1955 he worked for the International Pacific Salmon
Fisheries Commission, which regulated the Canadian and U.S. catch
of salmon from the Fraser. In his last five years with the agency
he was chief engineer and assistant director.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955 he became executive director of the newly formed North
Pacific commission, which included Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 he moved to Rome to direct worldwide fisheries
activities for the United Nations, and eight years later took the
No. 2 job in the Food and Agricultural Organization.
William Dale Jennings:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- William Dale Jennings, a pioneering gay
activist who co-founded the first major homosexual rights
organization in the United States, died May 11 of respiratory
failure. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings wrote ''The Cowboys,'' a novel later made into a movie
starring John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings helped found the Mattachine Society in the early 1950s
after he was charged with indecent behavior in a park. He was
acquitted by a jury in what was seen as a rebuke of police tactics
that entrapped homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mattachine Society dissolved a few years later, it
helped create the foundation for other homosexual rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings also co-founded ONE Magazine, the nation's first gay
publication. The postmaster began confiscating the magazine in
1954, contending it was obscene. It led to a landmark lawsuit that
culminated in a 1958 Supreme Court ruling that a publication
dedicated to homosexual equality was not obscene.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings also wrote two other novels, ''The Ronin'' and ''The
Sinking of the Sarah Diamond.''
Loyd Jowers:
</P>
<P>
   UNION CITY, Tenn. (AP) -- Loyd Jowers, the former Memphis cafe
owner who claimed he hired someone other than James Earl Ray to
assassinate Martin Luther King Jr., died Saturday of lung cancer.
He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers ran Jim's Grill, a cafe on the ground floor of a rooming
house from which prosecutors say the shot that killed King was
fired on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Ray confessed to the killing in 1969 but recanted and spent the
rest of his life trying to prove his innocence. He died in prison
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In an ABC-TV interview in 1993, Jowers said he received $100,000
from late Memphis produce merchant Frank Liberto to arrange King's
murder. He claimed he hired the assassin, but said it wasn't Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers and ''unknown conspirators'' were found liable in
December in a wrongful death lawsuit brought against Jowers by the
slain civil rights leader's family.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded the Kings just $100 in damages, but the family
had asked only for a token amount because what they wanted most was
for the jury to find evidence of a conspiracy in an effort to call
for a new investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers was sick for much of the trial and did not testify.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby County prosecutor John Campbell, who has investigated the
assassination, has said Jowers' claims had no merit.
</P>
<P>
   A House committee concluded in 1978 that Ray killed King but may
have had help from a small group of racists before or after the
murder. The committee found no government involvement.
Gary Osborn:
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Gary Osborn, the women's track and cross
country coach at Drake University and a member of the school's
coaching staff for 32 years, died Sunday of a heart attack. He was
56.
</P>
<P>
   He had been the longest-serving track coach in the Missouri
Valley Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn became an assistant coach at the school after graduating
in 1968. He was hired as women's cross country coach in 1989 and
was appointed women's track coach in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   His cross country teams won Missouri Valley Conference
championships in 1994, 1995 and 1998. He was the league's coach of
the year three times and was Gateway Conference coach of the year
in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 2051 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans back bill to bar census sampling in redistricting  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Choosing between actual enumeration and
statistical sampling might sound like a high school word problem,
but both sides say how census data are used when drawing
legislative districts will affect residents across the state.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Assembly's State Government Committee voted along
party lines, 3-2, to move a bill that would force the New Jersey
Apportionment Commission to use the actual count and disregard any
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   When the once-a-decade results are in, the commission is
required to use the numbers from the U.S. Census Bureau to draw
boundaries for state and federal representatives.
</P>
<P>
   However, the federal government will provide the state with two
figures: the actual head count of residents who answered the census
and an estimate based on that data and statistical models.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Republicans want the commission to only use the head
count, or actual enumeration.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and other opponents say to do that will undercut the
number of minorities, recent immigrants and city residents who
appear not likely to respond to the census. The only fair way, they
argue, is to use the statistical sample. They claim it presents a
more accurate picture of the state's population.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that sampling-enhanced numbers
cannot be used in congressional apportionment, the process by which
the House of Representative's 435 seats are distributed among the
states. Left unspecified was whether sample-adjusted numbers could
be used to allocate federal funds or to draw political boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   States will have the option of using either adjusted or raw
census data to redraw congressional and state legislative district
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bill sponsor, Assemblyman Michael P. Carroll, R-Morris, said New
Jersey's small towns and cities make it easier for census workers
to actually count residents. Using estimates would force the
redistricting commission to guess where people are living, Carroll
argued.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you don't know where they are, you can't draw district
lines to include them,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where do you put these people if you have no clue where they
are,'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll and other supporters said the state would be free to use
estimates when applying for federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted criticism from U.S. Rep. Frank Pallone, D-Long
Branch, who said the bill would limit the opportunity for
minorities and others in cities to be represented in government.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that what you're saying is that the right to vote is
less important than the money,'' Pallone said.
</P>
<P>
   Pallone said the only proven formula for an accurate count of
the population is to incorporate the statistical sample.
Republicans in Congress deny that, in part, so the number of
minorities will not be accurately reflected in urban districts, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're really talking about here is ultimately
discrimination,'' Pallone said. But he told the Assembly panel that
he did not think such politics played a role in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Nicholas Asselta, R-Cumberland, said the issue is
similar to voter turnout in elections. Elected officials complain
that more people should vote so more can take part in the process,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For minorities and others not likely to be counted, the message
should be to participate, Asselta said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want to stand up, stand up and fill out the census
form,'' Asselta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 2051 </TRAILER>
