<HEADLINE> Investigation of deadly pier collapse delayed  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- An engineering firm hired by the city to
investigate last week's deadly pier collapse will be replaced
because it previously performed work on the pier, the city said.
</P>
<P>
   S.T. Hudson Engineers Inc. of Camden, N.J., was supposed to
begin inspecting the wreckage Monday but disclosed that it had a
potential conflict of interest, said city spokeswoman Barbara
Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have decided to go with another firm,'' she said. ''With
the case still under investigation, what we're trying to avoid is
any appearance of impropriety with them having worked on the pier
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The city replaced Hudson with Urban Engineers Inc. of
Philadelphia, and Hudson met with Urban to turn over its files on
the case. Hudson executives did not return calls for comment
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were killed and another 37 injured Thursday night
when the pier supporting the new nightclub Heat crashed into the
Delaware River. Two people remained unaccounted for, but police
said they have not received any missing persons reports from people
claiming their loved ones were at the club.
</P>
<P>
   Killed were DeAnn White, 25, of Philadelphia; Jean Ferraro, 27,
of Cherry Hill, N.J.; and Monica Rodriguez, 21, also of Cherry
Hill. All were employees at the New Jersey State Aquarium in
Camden.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro's funeral is scheduled for Tuesday and Rodriguez is to
be buried Wednesday. Funeral arrangements for White remained
incomplete. The aquarium is planning a small, private memorial
service for the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Under rainy skies Monday, investigators from the police crime
scene unit and the Licenses and Inspections Department continued to
comb through the wreckage as a crane hoisted large chunks of wood
from the cool, murky water. Debris is being taken to Fort Mifflin
for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, an attorney for one of the owners tried to gain
access to the scene but was turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Shawn Dougherty of the police Marine Unit said police
divers won't be going into the water anytime soon because more of
the pier could tumble into the river at any time. ''That's how
insecure it is,'' Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Underwater cameras have already documented chairs, potted
plants, refrigerators, fuel lines and other items from the club.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the Philadelphia Daily News, quoting police
sources, reported that the operators of Pier 34 knew about its
structural problems for at least eight years. Police searched for
evidence in the offices of Eli Karetny, the nightclub's owner.
</P>
<P>
   Karetny did not return a call for comment Monday. The office of
his lawyer, Robert Lane, referred calls to a partner at his firm,
who did not immediately return a call.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the pier, real estate developer Michael Asbell,
said his lawyers advised him not to comment on the investigation
but called the media reports ''outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're sick and saddened'' about the deaths. ''I can't tell you
how terrible we feel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an ongoing investigation. We're cooperating with all
the agencies. Pending this investigation, we're not at liberty to
talk about it,'' Asbell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-22-00 2057 </TRAILER>
