<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Commonwealth 4, Tennessee 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Unseeded Virginia Commonwealth and perennial
champion Stanford advanced to the finals of the NCAA men's tennis
championships Monday, eliminating two Southeastern Conference
schools.
</P>
<P>
   VCU trailed Tennessee 4-3, but won when two Volunteers players
retired with cramps.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford shut out Florida 4-0, but was forced to three sets in
every singles match except one.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's finals matchup includes VCU (27-4), a team that had
never advanced beyond the round of 16, and Stanford (27-1), a team
that has won 16 team championships, including 12 of the last 15.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (23-6) led 3-2 when both Paul Podbury at No. 4 singles
and Peter Handoyo at No. 3 singles were forced to default within
minutes of each other, giving VCU (27-4) the 4-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   Podbury led Fernando Sanchez 7-5, 4-4 in a lengthy match at No.
4. Both players exchanged defensive groundstrokes and a few harsh
words. Sanchez lost the first set when he was called for two code
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Podbury could not serve in the ninth game of the second set and
retired, tying the team score 3-3, and shifting the attention to
the Jose Sanchez-Handoyo match.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at No. 3, Handoyo and Jose Sanchez were both showing
the signs of dehydration. After the eighth game of the third set,
Sanchez asked for a five-minute injury timeout so that ice bags
could be applied to his thighs. Between points, their coaches
rushed onto the court with water.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez double-faulted twice in the ninth game, but fought off a
break point, after which Handoyo requested an injury timeout in the
middle of a game. After the timeout, Sanchez held his serve to go
up 4-6, 6-1, 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   Handoyo used his full 90-second allotment during the crossover
to walk to the other end of the court. When he fell to his knees,
Tennessee coach Michael Fancutt signaled that Handoyo was retiring,
setting off a jubilant reaction from VCU.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was an ugly way to win,'' VCU coach Paul Kostin coach.
''I've never seen anything like it, and I have been coaching a few
years. You don't want to win it that way. It was a good match. It
was a shame it had to come down to a couple of defaults. It was not
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Fancutt also spoke of the unusual nature of the matches.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a hard way to lose,'' Fancutt said. ''Normally that
is not a hard decision when you see one of your guys struggling.
But both guys were pretty close to defaulting. Pete might have been
one shot away from winning. But when he couldn't even move, you
can't watch a guy you have worked with for two years not be able to
move.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure, it was difficult, because for the past three years we
have worked to get to where we are and to get to the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostin said he never considered pulling Jose Sanchez from his
match.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a strong kid,'' Kostin said. ''If we're going down, we're
going down fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee won the doubles point and got wins from Adam Carey at
No. 2 and from Mark Fitzpatrick at No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Commonwealth won with Daniel Andersson at No. 1 and
Mats Norin at No. 5. Andersson, the nation's second-ranked player,
beat Mark Parsons 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Florida relied on its doubles and a strong 1-2 punch with the
nation's top-ranked player Jeff Morrison at No. 1 singles and
10th-ranked Justin O'Neal at No. 2. But Stanford won the doubles,
and Cardinal ace Alex Kim, ranked seventh, defeated Morrison 6-3,
7-5, ending a 14-match win streak.
</P>
<P>
   ''Florida is flat-out a great team,'' Stanford coach Dick Gould
said. ''It took a great competitive effort on our part to get by
them. If we played them 10 times, Florida would win five times.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Florida forced a third set in five of six singles
matches, the Gators could not score a point. Stanford's K.J.
Hippensteel won at No. 3, and Scotty Scott clinched the match at
No. 5 with a 3-6, 6-3, 6-1 win over Dylan Mann.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
