<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Vows To Focus on Economy  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Expressing confidence he will be
re-elected, President Hugo Chavez promised Monday to concentrate on
rescuing Venezuela's faltering economy and move away from the
political confrontation that characterized his first 15 months in
office.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally televised speech Monday night outlining his
vision for his next six years in office, Chavez said his
''revolution'' has served as an escape valve for popular
frustrations that have been building up for years.
</P>
<P>
   He said that now that his movement has decimated the old
political order, the country should ''leave behind the explosive
phases'' of the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are obliged to build on top of the ruins that we have
inherited as a country,'' he told a crowd gathered a hotel in
downtown Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelans vote Sunday in national elections required by a new
constitution pushed through by Chavez last year that calls for most
public offices, including the presidency, to be ''re-legitimized''
through new balloting.
</P>
<P>
   The constitution extended presidential terms from five to six
years and introduced immediate re-election for the first time --
giving Chavez the possibility of ruling for another 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls show the president with a 15- to 20-point lead over
his closest challenger, former Zulia state governor Francisco Arias
Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez and Arias led a failed 1992 coup attempt together, but
Arias has broken away from the president, saying he has betrayed
the original goals of their rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's opponents say he has spent too much time consolidating
power instead of dealing with the economy, which shrank by seven
percent last year despite a boom in international oil prices. They
say Chavez's constant verbal attacks on opposition politicians,
businessmen and Catholic church leaders have created a hostile
climate for investment.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez spent much of his speech Monday night explaining why his
government's economic policies are sensible, saying he was going to
personally command the economy's recovery and insisting he was not
opposed to private capital as his critics have claimed.
</P>
<P>
   But he reiterated that economic growth must be accompanied by
more equitable distribution of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last year's precipitous economic decline, there are
signs of a mild recovery with the central bank announcing last week
that the economy grew by a modest three-tenths of a percent in the
year's first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez also said he was committed to the democratic rule of law.
In the same breath, however, he offered Libya as a model for such a
democracy because of Moammar Gadhafi's use of ''popular assemblies
all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has been criticized for what his opponents say is
his sacrificing of good relations with the United States and
Colombia -- Venezuela's main trading partners -- in favor of boosting
ties to Cuba, China and Middle Eastern oil producing nations.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, two Venezuelan civil rights groups formally asked the
country's highest court to postpone the May 28 vote because of
confusion and technical difficulties in the electoral process. The
petition comes just days after the head of the Organization of
American States observation team in Venezuela expressed concern
that computer glitches could create problems during the elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
