<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Disbarment Recommendation Wrong
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton today decried an Arkansas Supreme
Court panel's recommendation that he should be disbarred over ''serious
misconduct'' in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case. He told ''NBC Nightly
News'' the panel responded too harshly to his testimony on Monica Lewinsky,
which he has labeled as ''legally accurate.'' Clinton attorney David Kendall
said of the recommendation: ''We will vigorously dispute it in a court of law.''
If a Little Rock judge now decides to disbar Clinton, the president can appeal
to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Astronauts Float Into Space Station
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Atlantis' astronauts floated into
the international space station tonight to replace dying batteries. American
astronaut Susan Helms and Russian cosmonaut Yuri Usachev led the way through a
dark vestibule into the brightly lit Unity module. Upon entering the station
from the joined shuttle, the seven crew members took air samples and tested the
carbon-dioxide level to make sure it was safe. No one had ventured inside the
station in a full year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FTC Asks For Web Privacy Laws
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a reversal of policy, the Federal Trade Commission
today asked Congress for new authority to regulate how companies use personal
information collected on their Web sites. The commission recommended that
lawmakers pass legislation to bolster its ability to oversee online privacy,
concluding that the industry has failed to safeguard consumer privacy through
self-regulation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Railroad Killer Sentenced to Death
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- The admitted railroad killer who made the FBI's 10 Most
Wanted List was sentenced today to death for killing a Houston-area doctor, one
of nine murders he was accused of committing. The jury that convicted Angel
Maturino Resendiz last week met for just less than two hours before deciding on
the death sentence. It could have sentenced the Mexican drifter to life in
prison. He had asked for the death penalty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Seeks Backing on Lebanon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Israel's security belt inside southern Lebanon
collapsed Monday, Prime Minister Ehud Barak sought the help of the United States
and the United Nations for a peaceful pullout of Israeli troops. Israeli-allied
militiamen, who helped maintain the security zone for 22 years, fled toward
Israel's border. Hundreds of Lebanese civilians rushed forward to fill the
vacuum. Barak said he would hold Syria and Lebanon accountable if the Israeli
withdrawal was marked by violence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Rescuer Sues Over Raid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The man photographed holding Elian Gonzalez during the armed
raid in which the 6-year-old Cuban refugee was seized is suing federal
government officials, saying his constitutional rights were violated. The
federal lawsuit filed by Donato Dalrymple seeks damages in excess of $100
million. ''The complaint alleges unnecessary and excessive physical force,''
said Tom Fitton, president of Judicial Watch, a conservative group that is
providing legal representation for Dalrymple. Dalrymple helped to rescue Elian
from the Atlantic last Thanksgiving.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Ousts Cable TV Sex Rules
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the name of free speech, the Supreme Court struck down
a federal law that shielded children from sex-oriented cable TV channels. By a
5-4 vote, the court said Congress cannot require cable operators to restrict
sexually explicit programming to overnight hours as a way of minimizing the
chance that partially audible or visible snippets reach children. The decision
ended a dispute over regulating cable systems that fail to fully scramble
signals for nonsubscribers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Americans Eat Out In Record Numbers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Wealthier than ever, Americans are dining out in record
numbers, spending $1 billion a day in restaurants and on prepared meals from
supermarkets. The restaurant industry is expected to generate $376 billion in
sales this year, up 5 percent from 1999, according to the National Restaurant
Association.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 84; Nasdaq Off 26
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The stock market finished moderately lower today after
recovering from punishing losses during a volatile session. The Dow Jones
industrial average plunged over 250 points before finishing down 84.30 at
10,542.55. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,778-1,164. The Nasdaq, which was
down nearly 218 points to its low for the year, finished off 26.19 at 3,364.21.
Nervousness over high-tech stocks was blamed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Brewers Sweep Astros
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Milwaukee Brewers made the biggest ninth-inning
comeback in their history in the first game of a doubleheader today, scoring
seven runs in the ninth before Jose Hernandez's solo homer in the 10th beat the
Houston Astros 10-9. In the second game, Jeromy Burnitz hit a three-run homer
and Jason Bere pitched eight strong innings as the Brewers swept the twinbill
with a 6-1 victory.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER
</SUBHEAD>
