<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Alberta Hospitals Prepare for Strike
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Thousands of patients were affected
Monday as hospitals across Alberta prepared for a massive illegal
strike by juggling surgeries and looking at who they could send
home early.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term care centers and psychiatric facilities were also
getting ready as the clock ticked down to a Wednesday deadline set
by 10,000 health workers who intend to walk off the job if deals
can't be reached by then.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Alberta Labor Relations Board ordered the Alberta
Union of Provincial Employees to ''cease and desist'' in its threat
to strike at 159 hospitals and continuing care centers across the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Union president Dan MacLennan, who says the labor board is no
friend to workers, said they will not obey the order. It would be
the largest strike in the history of the province's largest union.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Victoria Day Weekend Marred by Accidents
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- The Victoria Day long weekend, traditionally a
time when winter-weary Canadians celebrate the coming of summer,
was marred by several deaths this year, including a promising
Prairie hockey player who died during a wilderness adventure and
two scientists who perished in a helicopter crash in a remote area
of Nunavut.
</P>
<P>
   In Saskatchewan and Manitoba, hockey fans were stunned to hear
that 19-year-old Kyle Johnson, a promising junior player was found
dead early Saturday evening in a rugged forested area northwest of
Kenora, Ontario
</P>
<P>
   The Winnipeg teen, a forward with the Melfort Mustangs of the
Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League, led the league with 46 goals
this season.
</P>
<P>
   He had been part of a group of 18- to 23-year-olds on a
wilderness vacation tour. The company that runs the tours said only
that ''an unfortunate incident,'' that led to the teen's death.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern community of Resolute, Nunavut, two scientists
doing research on polar bears were killed Sunday when their
helicopter crashed, shattering into pieces. The victims were not
identified.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Illness to 78-Year-Old Rocket Richard Stirs Concern
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Gloomy reports that Maurice ''Rocket'' Richard
was on his death bed during the weekend once again drew attention
to how revered the hockey legend is in his home province.
</P>
<P>
   At a hastily called news conference at Hotel Dieu hospital on
Sunday, Dr. Andre Robidoux had a calming message.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-year-old Richard's cancer had not spread throughout his
body, he was not semi-comatose and he did not also have Alzheimer's
disease, said Robidoux, shooting down a week's worth of
panic-tinged reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket remains very ill, he said. A cancerous tumor in his
abdomen that first appeared nearly three years ago had recurred and
doctors were monitoring his condition to see what treatment they
could use.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital did not provide new information on Richard's
condition Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rocket is a hockey legend across Canada, he's more
than that in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Richard once insisted: ''I'm not a politician, I'm just a hockey
player.'' But for many, he is a symbol of French-Canadian pride and
accomplishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
