<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nedrow man pleads innocent to arson  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- An Onondaga County man pleaded innocent
Monday to charges that he set a barn fire and killed 12 horses last
December.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Furgal, 19, is accused of pouring gasoline on the barn at
Quarry Ridge Stables in Nedrow. Furgal worked as a laborer at the
stables, and the owner provided him with food and a place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Furgal set the fire because he was angry at Lori Lorini, who
owned the horses, and her friend. Lorini rented the barn for $400 a
month from Quarry Road Stables, a sprawling horse farm just south
of Syracuse owned by Phil Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Furgal initially told deputies the
fire was an accident and that the flames erupted while he was
splashing gasoline on an incinerator next to the barn. He later
admitted he intentionally set the barn ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   But he claimed he never intended to hurt the horses.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by 1,500 bales of hay stored inside for the winter, the
fire turned the barn into a roaring inferno that took 100
firefighters from seven suburban departments four hours to bring
under control. Furgal stood with a crowd and watched the barn burn.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the barn housed as many as 19 horses but the
remains of only 12 of the animals were found after the fire was
extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Furgal faces up to 24 years in prison. He's being held at the
Onondaga County Justice Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
