<HEADLINE> McCain Preaches Unity at GOP Dinner  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0152-----
r p *1131AP-McCain     05-22 0257
*1131 AP-McCain,0256   
McCain Preaches Unity at GOP Dinner
AP Photos CTDH101-102
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Saying that ''now is the time for
unity,'' Sen. John McCain urged supporters attending a state
Republican Party fund-raiser Monday night to join him in helping to
elect George W. Bush as president.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican earned a standing ovation when he said
his former rival for the GOP presidential nomination would restore
integrity and purpose to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask all McCain supporters to join me in helping elect
Governor George Bush,'' McCain said. ''Now is the time for unity.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was the keynote speaker at the Prescott Bush Award
Dinner, named for Bush's late grandfather, a Greenwich Republican
and U.S. senator. The event raised about $250,000 from more than
900 Republicans who paid $200 per plate and $1,000 to attend a
private, predinner reception.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won Connecticut's primary March 7 but dropped from the
race after losses in other states that night. He said he did not
have trouble speaking at an event full of Bush supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to move forward and not look back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also drew laughs by noting that he joined Barry Goldwater
and other unsuccessful presidential candidates from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ''Arizona may be the only state in America where mothers don't
tell their children someday they may grow up to become president of
the United States,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
