<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain preached unity, reform at GOP dinner  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- U.S. Sen John McCain preached unity,
reform and the need to win over new voters at the state Republican
party's biggest annual fund-raiser Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican sparked a standing ovation when he said
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, his former rival for the Republican
nomination for president, would restore integrity and purpose to
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask all McCain supporters to join me in helping elect Gov.
George Bush,'' McCain said. ''Now is the time for unity.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was the keynote speaker at the Prescott Bush Award
Dinner. The fund-raiser, named for Gov. Bush's late grandfather, a
Greenwich Republican who served in the U.S. Senate, attracted more
than 900 republicans and raised about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland, who served in Congress with McCain, said
the senator's lobbying efforts for congressional candidates
nationwide would help Republicans maintain majorities in the House
and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who won Connecticut's March 7 primary but was forced to
drop out of the race after losses in other Super Tuesday primaries,
said his supporters would serve as delegates but ultimately support
Bush at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged he still has differences with Bush, but said
the candidate has campaigned well in recent months. He said Bush's
centrist message on education and health care have helped improve
his standing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he did not have trouble speaking at an event full of
Bush supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to move forward and not look back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He drew laughs when he noted that he joined Barry Goldwater and
other unsuccessful presidential candidates from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ''Arizona may be the only state in America where mothers don't
tell their children someday they may grow up to become president of
the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who attracted many Democrats and Independents his
campaign, said the party needs the support of new voters to be
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our party should always broaden our base,'' he said. ''The
country is best served by a party that seeks to represent fairly
the dreams of all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said reforms are needed in education, the military and
the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   He accused President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore of
campaign finance abuses, saying they treated the Lincoln bedroom
like a Motel 6.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees paid $200 per plate and $1,000 for a private reception
before the dinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
