<HEADLINE> Notes From Monday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
White Sox-Blue Jays:
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The White Sox have lost just two of their last 10 games
at SkyDome. ... The White Sox are in the midst of a 38-game stretch
where they play 22 games against the New York Yankees and Cleveland
Indians. ... Frank Thomas went 6-for-13 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Toronto's last three wins have been in their last
at-bat. ... OF Todd Greene, released by the Anaheim Angels in
spring training, made his first appearance for Toronto. He went
1-for-3. .. Craig Grebeck has 15 hits in his last 38 at-bats. ...
Billy Koch is 9-for-12 in save opportunities.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Astros-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: The Astros were scheduled for two trips to Milwaukee,
both in the first seven weeks of the 2000 season. Rainouts last
week forced the team to return from a disappointing weekend in
Montreal, which swept the three-game series. ''Besides the fact
that we lost every game, what I'll remember is all the rain,''
manager Larry Dierker said as rain prevented batting practice prior
to Monday's doubleheader at County Stadium. ''You don't have to go
to South America to see the rain forest, just come up here. At
least it's not cold this time.'' ... Stuck in last place after
figuring to contend for the NL's Central Division title, Dierker
said it would be some feat to come back and win it. ''We've dug
this hole deep enough that we're now a longshot,'' he said. ''I
think we still could do it, but it's going to be hard.''
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers optioned reliever Horacio Estrada (2-0,
6.63 ERA) to Triple-A Indianapolis and recalled P Rafael Roque, 4-2
with a 5.86 ERA in seven starts at Indianapolis. ... The Brewers
started the week with two hitters above the .300 mark in SS Mark
Loretta (.307) and 2B Ron Belliard (.302).
Reds-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Reliever Mark Wohlers, working his way back to the
majors from a torn ligament in his elbow -- and a severe bout with
wildness -- will throw live batting practice on Wednesday and is
expected to make his first rehab assignment on May 29 with Class A
Dayton. ''He's in a great frame of mind,'' Reds pitching coach Don
Gullett said. ''His mechanics now are as sound as they've ever
been, and he looks like the old Mark Wohlers when he was with
Atlanta. He's been throwing his split-finger and his slider for the
last couple of weeks, and the intensity is getting better. So we
anticipate him making a full recovery and helping the Cincinnati
Reds in the very near future.'' ... Denny Neagle carried a streak
of 10 consecutive winning decisions into Monday night's start
against the Dodgers. The streak spanned 16 starts. He was 12-2
since July 30 of last season, when he finished a stretch of more
than two months on the disabled list because of weakness in his
pitching shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Trever Miller, the left-handed reliever whom the
Los Angeles Dodgers obtained on waivers from Philadelphia last
Friday, was activated on Monday and expressed joy over his change
of scenery. ''I love it,'' he said. ''This team has a very
legitimate chance of going to the playoffs and the World Series,
from what I've seen. In Philadelphia, we basically had no chance.
They're in such a hole right now, I don't think they can possible
find their way out of it. Maybe they can get back to .500 baseball,
but they're not going to go to the playoffs.'' The Phillies come to
Dodger Stadium on Friday for a three-game weekend series. ... CF
Devon White, who has been out since May 5 after partially tearing
his left rotator cuff while diving for a ball, was re-examined on
Monday. ''I think they were talking about giving him 30 days' rest
and then another MRI to see how the partial tear is coming,''
manager Davey Johnson said. ''Hopefully, it's going to be better.
And if it is, then he's probably past the point where they might
have to do something more drastic.'' ... Reliever Mike Fetters, who
hasn't pitched since May 3 because of a sore right elbow, showed no
adverse effects from his 50-pitch session in the bullpen on Sunday.
He is expected to throw again on Tuesday and be ready for duty on
Friday.
Mets-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: OF Melvin Mora began a rehabilitation assignment
Monday night with Triple-A Norfolk of the International League,
which started a four-game series with Pawtucket. Mora was placed on
the disabled list on May 13 with a cut on his right index finger.
He is eligible to come off the DL on May 28. ... 1B Todd Zeile got
the night off and Matt Franco got the start.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: RHP Carlton Loewer pitched a three-inning simulated
game of about 60 pitches and did well, manager Bruce Bochy said.
He'll probably throw on the side once more and then begin a rehab
assignment on Friday. Loewer began the season on the disabled list
with a broken left ankle suffered when he fell out of a deer blind
while hunting in January. ... The Padres signed RHP Carlos Reyes to
a minor league contract and assigned him to Triple-A Las Vegas.
Reyes returns to the Padres' organization for the third time. He
was with Philadelphia earlier this year. ... 3B Phil Nevin was
named NL Player of the Week after hitting .667 (14-for-21) with
three doubles, a triple and four homers, including his first career
grand slam. He drove in 14 runs and scored seven runs. ... RF Tony
Gwynn was back in the lineup after sitting out two games due to his
troublesome left knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
