<DOCNO> APW20000522.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Don't Agree On Nazi Fund  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and German negotiators failed on Monday
to finish work on a system to compensate Nazi-era slave laborers,
complicating plans for President Clinton to sign an agreement
during his upcoming visit to Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat and head German
negotiator Otto Lambsdorff worked for several hours on the plan,
which would set up a German foundation to pay claims to former
forced and slave laborers as well as some other Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to travel to Berlin the first week of June, and
negotiators had hoped a completed agreement could be signed then by
him and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   But Eizenstat said another round of negotiations by a small
working group would be held in Berlin on May 31 and a session with
the wider group of negotiators would be held in late June.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am hopeful that we will resolve all remaining issues and
plan a concluding ... session late in June,'' Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of issues remain to be worked out, including one wanted
by German companies to preclude further lawsuits against them in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   German businesses suggested the foundation after several
class-action suits were brought against them in the United States.
The German government and industry agreed to come up with $5
billion for the fund under the condition that further suits will
not be entertained in U.S. courts.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement has been under negotiation for more than a year by
the two nations, German industry, five Central and Eastern European
countries where the majority of survivors live, Israel, lawyers
from the class action suits and other representatives of survivors.
At times there have been some 90 people involved in negotiating
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We certainly remain optimistic that this will be signed in the
near future,'' said Gideon Taylor, executive vice president of the
Conference on Jewish Material Claims Against Germany, one of the
negotiating groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-22-00 2314 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000522.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-22 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mistakes Prove Costly For Flyers  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Flyers got sloppy and the
New Jersey Devils got back in the series.
</P>
<P>
   With history on its side, Philadelphia failed to close out New
Jersey on Monday night and let momentum shift back to the Devils in
the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey capitalized on crucial miscues and beat the Flyers
4-1 in Game 5 to cut Philadelphia's lead in the best-of-seven
series to 3-2. Game 6 is Wednesday at the Continental Airlines
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ''They won every battle.'' Flyers forward Rick Tocchet said.
''They had stuff we never gave them before, 2-on-1 breaks,
breakaways. They played smart and we didn't adjust. We kept making
the same mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey scored its first goal when the Flyers failed to clear
the puck on a power play despite several opportunities to ice it.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott blasted a shot past Brian Boucher two seconds
before Kent Manderville left the penalty box for a 1-0 lead midway
through the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ''I should've cleared the puck. It was my mistake,'' forward
Valeri Zelepukin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik made it 2-0 five minutes later when Keith Primeau
couldn't control an errant outlet pass, setting up an odd-man rush.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher was helpless as Holik broke in with Jay Pandolfo and
Vladimir Malakhov. It was the first time in the series that either
team took a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our players were trying to create something and none of it
worked,'' Flyers interim coach Craig Ramsay said. ''It was one of
those nights. We tried some things that didn't work and when you
fall behind, you try a little more. Nothing worked for us.''
</P>
<P>
   After a nifty goal by Zelepukin cut it to 3-1 late in the second
period, New Jersey regained its three-goal lead following a
giveaway by John LeClair less than a minute into the third.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair's errant pass in neutral ice went right to Patrik Elias,
who skated in and beat Boucher between the pads with a backhander.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did a poor job of forcing the puck through the neutral
zone,'' LeClair said. ''We did a lot of things we said we couldn't
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve teams in the last 12 years have come back from a 3-1
deficit to win a playoff series, but all 12 teams did it in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen teams in NHL history have come back from either a 3-1 or
3-0 deficit, but none have done it since the NHL expanded in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time New Jersey has forced a sixth game after
trailing 3-1. The Devils fell behind 3-1 twice before and lost both
series in five.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they were ever out of the series,'' defenseman
Dan McGillis said. ''They're not going to lay down and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, New Jersey has never come back from a 3-2 deficit either.
The Devils are 0-4 when trailing 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever we did tonight is great, but it's over and it doesn't
mean anything,'' Holik said. ''The game on Wednesday is our
season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
