<HEADLINE> SLA Judge Threatens Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A judge threatened a retired policeman's
lawyer with sanctions for openly filing a lawsuit against a woman
accused of attempting to kill officers with pipe bombs in a 1975
Symbionese Liberation Army plot.
</P>
<P>
   With a gag order issued in the case against Sara Jane Olson,
Superior Court Judge James M. Ideman told attorney Bradley Gage
Monday that he should have filed the lawsuit under seal.
</P>
<P>
   Ideman called the filing ''a breathtaking act of chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   Gage said he believed he followed the judge's order barring
lawyers and witnesses from speaking about the case outside court.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit by former Officer James Bryan claims Olson planted
bombs under his patrol car while he and his partner were eating at
a restaurant 25 years ago. The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages
for emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal case against Olson, 53, alleges pipe bombs were
planted under Bryan's car and another police car as revenge for the
deaths of six SLA members in a shootout with police. The bombs did
not go off.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly known as Kathleen Ann Soliah, Olson was arrested last
year in St. Paul, Minn. She had married a doctor, had three
children and was active in her community.
</P>
</TEXT>
