<HEADLINE> Detroit Drops Larry Murphy's Option  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- The Detroit Red Wings have chosen not to exercise
a $3 million team option on veteran defenseman Larry Murphy's
contract for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a case of economics, as it is the case in professional
sports often these days,'' general manager Ken Holland, who wants
to work out a less expensive deal, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, 39, had 10 goals and 30 assists in 81 games during the
regular season. He added two goals and three assists in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy earned $2.5 million this season. He would become an
unrestricted free agent July 1 if he doesn't come to terms with the
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to have Larry Murphy play for us,'' Holland, who
will meet with Murphy later this week, told The Detroit News for a
story Tuesday. ''I think he can help our team. Hopefully, we'll be
able to work something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was unavailable for comment Monday.
</P>
